{"title_page": "Chris Parry (producer)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Chris Parry\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = John Christopher Parry\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1949|1|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lower Hutt]], [[New Zealand]]\n| instrument       = drums\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = {{hlist|record producer|manager|musician}}\n| years_active     = 1967\u20132001, 2010\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[The Fourmyula]]|[[The Jam]]|[[The Cure]]}}\n}}\n\n'''John Christopher Parry''',<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Apter|first=Jeff|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Y6O0Pv8aG44C&pg=PT80&dq=%22john+christopher+parry%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiMpfGVrODoAhXOiFwKHed1AaQQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20christopher%20parry%22&f=false|title=Never Enough: The Story of The Cure|date=2009-11-05|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-024-3|language=en}}</ref> known as '''Chris Parry''' (born 7 January 1949), is a New Zealand  [[record producer]] and former [[musician]], known for being the manager and producer for [[The Cure]] for more than 20 years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.audioculture.co.nz/people/chris-parry|title=Chris Parry - AudioCulture|website=www.audioculture.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nParry was born in [[Lower Hutt]], [[New Zealand]]; the son of Virginia and Thomas, who was British. He grew up with ten siblings<ref name=\":0\" />: five sisters (Virginia, Margaret, Josephine, Annette and Helen) and five brothers (David, James Richard, Robin and Peter). In 1966, Parry was a management trainee at [[Philips|Philips Electrical]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/headliner-rock-n-roll-survivor-starts-rejuvenate-londons-airwaves-sh-failed-drummer-a-r-man-xfm-chief-chris-parry-talks-radio-claire-beale/27302?preferredformat=mobile|title=HEADLINER: Rock 'n' roll survivor starts to rejuvenate London's airwaves. Failed drummer, A&R man and Xfm chief Chris Parry talks radio to Claire Beale.|last=|first=|date=24 January 1997|website=campaignlive.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1967, whilst studying at [[Silverstream College]], Parry auditioned as [[drummer]] for a band called the Sine Waves, who later renamed themselves [[the Fourmyula]]. He has stated \u201cI got the job because I had a truck driver\u2019s licence\u201d.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://thisnzlife.co.nz/nature-enter-chris-parrys-coromandel-home/|title=Nature enter me: Chris Parry's Coromandel home|date=2017-03-16|website=thisNZlife|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Within a year, the band had hit the charts, reaching number 2 in New Zealand with \"Come with Me\" and reached number 1 in 1969 with \"[[Nature (song)|Nature]]\". The band made two trips to the UK, but were not so successful there. After the band split in 1971, Parry returned to England and spent two years obtaining a diploma in marketing and advertising from the [[College for Distributive Trades]] in London.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/afternoons/audio/2018691244/new-zealander-chris-parry-on-managing-the-cure|title=New Zealander Chris Parry on managing The Cure|date=2019-04-16|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He then found a job in the International department at [[Phonogram Records]], under fellow New Zealander [[John McCready]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1974, Parry was offered a job at [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] in [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]]. His first signing was the [[Chanter Sisters|Chanter Sisters.]] [[Punk rock|Punk]] was in its early days but it was clear that it was going to be big, so Parry went to check out some of these bands. His requests to Polydor in 1976 to sign the Sex Pistols and the Clash were rejected.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, in January 1977, he got a tip from future-[[The Pogues|Pogues]] frontman [[Shane MacGowan]] to check out [[the Jam]]. Parry was convinced and signed them to Polydor in February. He also co-produced the Jam's first three albums as well as the only album by t[[The Jolt|he Jolt]] who he also signed. Later in 1977, he helped convince Polydor to sign [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]] after listening to [[Hong Kong Garden (song)|Hong Kong Garden]] from the [[BBC|BBC's]] [[John Peel|John Peel sessions]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1978, Parry began starting his own record label, which was later to be named [[Fiction Records|Fiction]], which was to be an imprint of Polydor, after becoming increasingly frustrated with Polydor not listening to his requests. He listened to a demo tape by [[the Cure]] and was particularly impressed with \"[[10:15 Saturday Night]]\" and also \"[[Boys Don't Cry (The Cure song)|Boys Don't Cry]]\". He called them up and a meeting was arranged for August at Polydor's office in [[Stratford Place]]. After the meeting, [[Robert Smith (singer)|Robert Smith]] invited Parry to watch them perform at the Laker's Hotel in [[Redhill, Surrey|Redhill]] on 27 August. After the gig, Parry invited them to a drink at a nearby pub, The Home Cottage, at which he told the Cure he wanted them to be his first signing, which they agreed to and they officially signed in September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recordcollectormag.com/articles/cure-ail-ail-rocknroll-alt-pops-aid-relief|title=Searching For The Cure - Record Collector Magazine|website=recordcollectormag.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Soon after, Parry signed [[Billy Mackenzie|Billy MacKenzie]] and [[Alan Rankine]], who went on to form [[The Associates (band)|the Associates]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Along with engineer [[Mike Hedges]], Parry then recorded the Cure's first album ''[[Three Imaginary Boys]]'' at [[Morgan Studios]], which was released in May 1979. The next three albums released were [[Purple Hearts (British band)|Purple Hearts']] ''Beat That!'', [[The Passions (British band)|the Passions']] ''[[Michael & Miranda]]'' and [[The Associates (band)|the Associates']] ''[[The Affectionate Punch|The Affectionate Bunch]]'', all in 1980.<ref name=\":1\" /> Parry managed the Cure until 1988 and Fiction released their music until 2001, when he sold the label to [[Universal Records]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Parry says he \"kind of retired from music if you like when I was 52 or 53 in 2001 when I sold everything out\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1992, along with Sammy Jacob, Parry launched [[radio station]] [[Xfm]] (rebranded as Radio X in 2015) in London. The left-field [[Alternative rock|alternative]] station was a \u201cmix between [[95bFM|bFM]] and early [[Radio Hauraki]]\u201d according to Parry, who was managing director. The station was sold to [[Capital Radio Group]] in 1998.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2010, The Fourmyula reformed in order to promote a box set release. With Parry reprising his role as drummer, they played two concerts in [[Auckland]] and [[Upper Hutt]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1971, Parry first got married to a woman from Scotland. About this he has said \"we were way too young\".<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1974, he became a father for the first time.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sometime between the 1990s, Parry had two more children with then partner Elaine. In 1996, he bought a property on the [[Coromandel Peninsula]], where he has been living since. He  remarried in around 2010. In 2016, he met Susan Verkerk, who has since been his partner.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parry, Chris}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand record producers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand drummers]]\n[[Category:Music managers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Hutt]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n{{EngvarB|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Chris Parry\n| image            = \n| image_size       = \n| landscape        = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = John Christopher Parry\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1949|1|7}}\n| birth_place      = [[Lower Hutt]], [[New Zealand]]\n| instrument       = drums\n| genre            = \n| occupation       = {{hlist|record producer|manager|musician}}\n| years_active     = 1967\u20132001, 2010\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[The Fourmyula]]|[[The Jam]]|[[The Cure]]}}\n}}\n\n'''John Christopher Parry''',<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=Apter|first=Jeff|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=Y6O0Pv8aG44C&pg=PT80&dq=%22john+christopher+parry%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiMpfGVrODoAhXOiFwKHed1AaQQ6AEIKjAA#v=onepage&q=%22john%20christopher%20parry%22&f=false|title=Never Enough: The Story of The Cure|date=2009-11-05|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-0-85712-024-3|language=en}}</ref> known as '''Chris Parry''' (born 7 January 1949), is a New Zealand  [[record producer]] and former [[musician]], known for being the manager and producer for [[The Cure]] for more than 20 years.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.audioculture.co.nz/people/chris-parry|title=Chris Parry - AudioCulture|website=www.audioculture.co.nz|language=en|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nParry was born in [[Lower Hutt]], [[New Zealand]]; the son of Virginia and Thomas, who was British. He grew up with ten siblings<ref name=\":0\" />: five sisters (Virginia, Margaret, Josephine, Annette and Helen) and five brothers (David, James Richard, Robin and Peter). In 1966, Parry was a management trainee at [[Philips|Philips Electrical]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.campaignlive.co.uk/article/headliner-rock-n-roll-survivor-starts-rejuvenate-londons-airwaves-sh-failed-drummer-a-r-man-xfm-chief-chris-parry-talks-radio-claire-beale/27302?preferredformat=mobile|title=HEADLINER: Rock 'n' roll survivor starts to rejuvenate London's airwaves. Failed drummer, A&R man and Xfm chief Chris Parry talks radio to Claire Beale.|last=|first=|date=24 January 1997|website=campaignlive.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1967, whilst studying at [[Silverstream College]], Parry auditioned as [[drummer]] for a band called the Sine Waves, who later renamed themselves [[the Fourmyula]]. He has stated \u201cI got the job because I had a truck driver\u2019s licence\u201d.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://thisnzlife.co.nz/nature-enter-chris-parrys-coromandel-home/|title=Nature enter me: Chris Parry's Coromandel home|date=2017-03-16|website=thisNZlife|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Within a year, the band had hit the charts, reaching number 2 in New Zealand with \"Come with Me\" and reached number 1 in 1969 with \"[[Nature (song)|Nature]]\". The band made two trips to the UK, but were not so successful there. After the band split in 1971, Parry returned to England and spent two years obtaining a diploma in marketing and advertising from the [[College for Distributive Trades]] in London.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rnz.co.nz/national/programmes/afternoons/audio/2018691244/new-zealander-chris-parry-on-managing-the-cure|title=New Zealander Chris Parry on managing The Cure|date=2019-04-16|website=RNZ|language=en-nz|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> He then found a job in the International department at [[Phonogram Records]], under fellow New Zealander [[John McCready]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 1974, Parry was offered a job at [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] in [[Artists and repertoire|A&R]]. His first signing was the [[Chanter Sisters|Chanter Sisters.]] [[Punk rock|Punk]] was in its early days but it was clear that it was going to be big, so Parry went to check out some of these bands. His requests to Polydor in 1976 to sign the Sex Pistols and the Clash were rejected.<ref name=\":0\" /> However, in January 1977, he got a tip from future-[[The Pogues|Pogues]] frontman [[Shane MacGowan]] to check out [[the Jam]]. Parry was convinced and signed them to Polydor in February. He also co-produced the Jam's first three albums as well as the only album by t[[The Jolt|he Jolt]] who he also signed. Later in 1977, he helped convince Polydor to sign [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]] after listening to [[Hong Kong Garden (song)|Hong Kong Garden]] from the [[BBC|BBC's]] [[John Peel|John Peel sessions]].<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1978, Parry began starting his own record label, which was later to be named [[Fiction Records|Fiction]], which was to be an imprint of Polydor, after becoming increasingly frustrated with Polydor not listening to his requests. He listened to a demo tape by [[the Cure]] and was particularly impressed with \"[[10:15 Saturday Night]]\" and also \"[[Boys Don't Cry (The Cure song)|Boys Don't Cry]]\". He called them up and a meeting was arranged for August at Polydor's office in [[Stratford Place]]. After the meeting, [[Robert Smith (singer)|Robert Smith]] invited Parry to watch them perform at the Laker's Hotel in [[Redhill, Surrey|Redhill]] on 27 August. After the gig, Parry invited them to a drink at a nearby pub, The Home Cottage, at which he told the Cure he wanted them to be his first signing, which they agreed to and they officially signed in September.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://recordcollectormag.com/articles/cure-ail-ail-rocknroll-alt-pops-aid-relief|title=Searching For The Cure - Record Collector Magazine|website=recordcollectormag.com|access-date=2020-04-11}}</ref> Soon after, Parry signed [[Billy Mackenzie|Billy MacKenzie]] and [[Alan Rankine]], who went on to form [[The Associates (band)|the Associates]].<ref name=\":0\" /> Along with engineer [[Mike Hedges]], Parry then recorded the Cure's first album ''[[Three Imaginary Boys]]'' at [[Morgan Studios]], which was released in May 1979. The next three albums released were [[Purple Hearts (British band)|Purple Hearts']] ''Beat That!'', [[The Passions (British band)|the Passions']] ''[[Michael & Miranda]]'' and [[The Associates (band)|the Associates']] ''[[The Affectionate Punch|The Affectionate Bunch]]'', all in 1980.<ref name=\":1\" /> Parry managed the Cure until 1988 and Fiction released their music until 2001, when he sold the label to [[Universal Records]].<ref name=\":1\" /> Parry says he \"kind of retired from music if you like when I was 52 or 53 in 2001 when I sold everything out\".<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nIn 1992, along with Sammy Jacob, Parry launched [[radio station]] [[Xfm]] (rebranded as Radio X in 2015) in London. The left-field [[Alternative rock|alternative]] station was a \u201cmix between [[95bFM|bFM]] and early [[Radio Hauraki]]\u201d according to Parry, who was managing director. The station was sold to [[Capital Radio Group]] in 1998.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nIn 2010, The Fourmyula reformed in order to promote a box set release. With Parry reprising his role as drummer, they played two concerts in [[Auckland]] and [[Upper Hutt]].<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n== Personal life ==\nIn 1971, Parry first got married to a woman from Scotland. About this he has said \"we were way too young\".<ref name=\":3\" /> In 1974, he became a father for the first time.<ref name=\":0\" /> Sometime between the 1990s, Parry had two more children with then partner Elaine. In 1996, he bought a property on the [[Coromandel Peninsula]], where he has lived since. He  remarried in around 2010. In 2016, he met Susan Verkerk, who has since been his partner.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parry, Chris}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:New Zealand record producers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand drummers]]\n[[Category:Music managers]]\n[[Category:New Zealand businesspeople]]\n[[Category:People from Lower Hutt]]\n", "name_user": "DPUH", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePersonal life", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Chris_Parry_(producer)"}
{"title_page": "Lyman J. Gage", "text_new": "{{short description|American financier and 42nd Secretary of the Treasury}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Lyman Gage\n|image       = Lyman Gage, Bain photo portrait.jpg\n|office      = 42nd [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]]\n|president   = [[William McKinley]]<br>[[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|term_start  = March 6, 1897\n|term_end    = January 31, 1902\n|predecessor = [[John G. Carlisle]]\n|successor   = [[L. M. Shaw|Leslie Shaw]]\n|birth_name  = Lyman Judson Gage\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1836|6|28}}\n|birth_place = [[DeRuyter, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1927|1|26|1836|6|28}}\n|death_place = [[San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] {{small|(Before 1884, 1896\u20131902)}}<br>[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] {{small|(1884\u20131896)}}\n}}\n'''Lyman Judson Gage''' (June 28, 1836 \u2013 January 26, 1927) was an [[Americans|American]] financier and [[Cabinet of the United States|Presidential Cabinet]] officer.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nHe was born in [[DeRuyter (town), New York|DeRuyter, New York]], educated at an academy in [[Rome, New York]], and at the age of 17 he became a bank clerk. In 1853 he removed to Chicago, served for three years as bookkeeper, and in 1858 entered the Merchants Loan and Trust Company, where he was cashier in 1861-1868. Afterwards be became successively assistant cashier, vice-president, and president of the [[First Chicago Bank|First National Bank of Chicago]], one of the strongest financial institutions in the [[Midwestern United States|Middle West]].\n\nHe was chosen in 1890 to be president of the board of directors of the [[World's Columbian Exposition]]. Following the exposition, he became president of the newly formed [[Chicago Civic Federation]], which sought to reform city governance.\n\n===Political career===\nIn politics he was originally a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]], and was a delegate to the national convention of the party in 1880, and chairman of its finance committee.\n\nIn 1884, however, he supported [[Grover Cleveland]] for the [[President of the United States|presidency]], and came to be looked upon as a Democrat. In 1892 President Cleveland, after his second election, offered Gage the post of secretary of the treasury, but Gage declined the offer. In the [[free silver|free-silver]] campaign of 1896, Gage labored effectively for the election of Republican candidate [[William McKinley]], and from March 1897 until January 1902 he served as [[Secretary of the Treasury]] in the cabinets successively of Presidents McKinley and [[Theodore Roosevelt]].\n\n[[File:GAGE, Lyman J-Treasury (BEP engraved portrait).jpg|thumb|left|[[Bureau of Engraving and Printing]] portrait of Gage as Secretary of the Treasury.]]\n\nAs Secretary of the Treasury, Gage was influential in securing passage of the [[Gold Standard Act]] of March 14, 1900, which reestablished a currency backed solely by gold. Since this limited the amount of [[currency]] in circulation, it initiated a period, continuing until 1912, in which the Secretary of Treasury was obliged to interact in the money market by introducing into circulation the Treasury surplus. The inability of the Treasury to respond to the needs of the market as well as the perceived need for a currency which would expand and contract with the needs of the nation, led to the creation of the [[Federal Reserve]] in 1913 to regulate the [[money market]].\n\nGage resigned in 1902 to become a banker in New York. From April 1902 until 1906 he was president of the [[United States Trust Company]] in [[New York City]]. His administration of the treasury department, through a more than ordinarily trying period, was marked by a conservative policy, looking toward the strengthening of the gold standard, the securing of greater flexibility in the currency, and a more perfect adjustment of the relations between the government and the National banks.\n\nLyman J Gage was instrumental in creating the San Diego [[Panama\u2013California Exposition]] of 1915. Later he was president of the committee to preserve the Expo's characteristic buildings in Balboa Park.\n\n===Final years===\nGage was one of the 30 founding members of the [[Simplified Spelling Board]], founded in 1906 by [[Andrew Carnegie]] to make English easier to learn and understand through changes in the [[orthography]] of the [[English language]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F02E5D6103EE733A25751C1A9659C946797D6CF&scp=1 \"CARNEGIE ASSAULTS THE SPELLING BOOK; To Pay the Cost of Reforming English Orthography. CAMPAIGN ABOUT TO BEGIN Board Named, with Headquarters Here -- Local Societies Throughout the Country.\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 12, 1906. Accessed August 28, 2008.</ref>\n\nHe died in [[San Diego]], [[California]], in 1927 and is buried at [[Rosehill Cemetery, Chicago|Rosehill Cemetery]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]].\n\n==Private life==\n[[File:Mrs Lyman J. Gage.jpg|thumb|left|Mrs. Cornelia Gage]]\nLyman Gage married Sarah Etheridge in 1864, and the couple had four children: Locke, Eli Alexander, Fanny, and Mary; only Eli survived to adulthood. Sarah died in 1874, when son Eli was 7 years old.  Eli Gage married Sophie R Weare in 1893 in Iowa, but committed suicide in Seattle in 1906 leaving his wife and two young sons, Lyman J. Gage II (1896-1954) and John Weare Gage (1900-1962).  After Sarah's death, Lyman Gage married Cornelia Lansing, who died childless in 1901. In late 1910s, Gage remarried a third time with Frances Ballou, and the two had a son, Lyman Judson. Frances died in 1943, around 16 years after Gage's death.\n\nIn 1906, Gage indulged his longtime interest in [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] phenomena by purchasing property on and subsequently living at [[Lomaland]], a [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophist]] retreat in Southern California. Though this came as something of a shock to the American public, those who knew him privately were not surprised, as Gage had previously studied [[spiritualism]], [[astrology]], and prophesied the death of his own brother through a \"[[psychic]] flash\".<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/chroniclingamerica/lccn/sn84026749/1906-07-15/ed-1/seq-48 Chronicling America - The Library of Congress<!-- bot-generated title -->] at www.loc.gov</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Gage, Lyman Judson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{U.S. Cabinet official box\n| before= [[John Griffin Carlisle|John G. Carlisle]]\n| after= [[L. M. Shaw|Leslie M. Shaw]]\n| years= March 6, 1897 \u2013 January 31, 1902\n| president= [[William McKinley]], [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n| department= Secretary of the Treasury}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USSecTreas}}\n{{McKinley cabinet}}\n{{T Roosevelt cabinet}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gage, Lyman, J.}}\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Burials at Rosehill Cemetery]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of the Treasury]]\n[[Category:Theodore Roosevelt administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:McKinley administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Rome, New York]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Lyman Gage\n|image       = Lyman Gage, Bain photo portrait.jpg\n|office      = 42nd [[United States Secretary of the Treasury]]\n|president   = [[William McKinley]]<br>[[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n|term_start  = March 6, 1897\n|term_end    = January 31, 1902\n|predecessor = [[John G. Carlisle]]\n|successor   = [[L. M. Shaw|Leslie Shaw]]\n|birth_name  = Lyman Judson Gage\n|birth_date  = {{birth date|1836|6|28}}\n|birth_place = [[DeRuyter, New York]], U.S.\n|death_date  = {{death date and age|1927|1|26|1836|6|28}}\n|death_place = [[San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n|party       = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] {{small|(Before 1884, 1896\u20131902)}}<br>[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] {{small|(1884\u20131896)}}\n}}\n'''Lyman Judson Gage''' (June 28, 1836 \u2013 January 26, 1927) was an [[Americans|American]] financier and [[Cabinet of the United States|Presidential Cabinet]] officer.\n\n==Biography==\n===Early life===\nHe was born in [[DeRuyter (town), New York|DeRuyter, New York]], educated at an academy in [[Rome, New York]], and at the age of 17 he became a bank clerk. In 1853 he removed to Chicago, served for three years as bookkeeper, and in 1858 entered the Merchants Loan and Trust Company, where he was cashier in 1861-1868. Afterwards be became successively assistant cashier, vice-president, and president of the [[First Chicago Bank|First National Bank of Chicago]], one of the strongest financial institutions in the [[Midwestern United States|Middle West]].\n\nHe was chosen in 1890 to be president of the board of directors of the [[World's Columbian Exposition]]. Following the exposition, he became president of the newly formed [[Chicago Civic Federation]], which sought to reform city governance.\n\n===Political career===\nIn politics he was originally a [[United States Republican Party|Republican]], and was a delegate to the national convention of the party in 1880, and chairman of its finance committee.\n\nIn 1884, however, he supported [[Grover Cleveland]] for the [[President of the United States|presidency]], and came to be looked upon as a Democrat. In 1892 President Cleveland, after his second election, offered Gage the post of secretary of the treasury, but Gage declined the offer. In the [[free silver|free-silver]] campaign of 1896, Gage labored effectively for the election of Republican candidate [[William McKinley]], and from March 1897 until January 1902 he served as [[Secretary of the Treasury]] in the cabinets successively of Presidents McKinley and [[Theodore Roosevelt]].\n\n[[File:GAGE, Lyman J-Treasury (BEP engraved portrait).jpg|thumb|left|[[Bureau of Engraving and Printing]] portrait of Gage as Secretary of the Treasury.]]\n\nAs Secretary of the Treasury, Gage was influential in securing passage of the [[Gold Standard Act]] of March 14, 1900, which reestablished a currency backed solely by gold. Since this limited the amount of [[currency]] in circulation, it initiated a period, continuing until 1912, in which the Secretary of Treasury was obliged to interact in the money market by introducing into circulation the Treasury surplus. The inability of the Treasury to respond to the needs of the market as well as the perceived need for a currency which would expand and contract with the needs of the nation, led to the creation of the [[Federal Reserve]] in 1913 to regulate the [[money market]].\n\nGage resigned in 1902 to become a banker in New York. From April 1902 until 1906 he was president of the [[United States Trust Company]] in [[New York City]]. His administration of the treasury department, through a more than ordinarily trying period, was marked by a conservative policy, looking toward the strengthening of the gold standard, the securing of greater flexibility in the currency, and a more perfect adjustment of the relations between the government and the National banks.\n\nLyman J Gage was instrumental in creating the San Diego [[Panama\u2013California Exposition]] of 1915. Later he was president of the committee to preserve the Expo's characteristic buildings in Balboa Park.\n\n===Final years===\nGage was one of the 30 founding members of the [[Simplified Spelling Board]], founded in 1906 by [[Andrew Carnegie]] to make English easier to learn and understand through changes in the [[orthography]] of the [[English language]].<ref>[https://query.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=9F02E5D6103EE733A25751C1A9659C946797D6CF&scp=1 \"CARNEGIE ASSAULTS THE SPELLING BOOK; To Pay the Cost of Reforming English Orthography. CAMPAIGN ABOUT TO BEGIN Board Named, with Headquarters Here -- Local Societies Throughout the Country.\"], ''[[The New York Times]]'', March 12, 1906. Accessed August 28, 2008.</ref>\n\nHe died in [[San Diego]], [[California]], in 1927 and is buried at [[Rosehill Cemetery, Chicago|Rosehill Cemetery]] in [[Chicago, Illinois|Chicago]].\n\n==Private life==\n[[File:Mrs Lyman J. Gage.jpg|thumb|left|Mrs. Cornelia Gage]]\nLyman Gage married Sarah Etheridge in 1864, and the couple had four children: Locke, Eli Alexander, Fanny, and Mary; only Eli survived to adulthood. Sarah died in 1874, when son Eli was 7 years old.  Eli Gage married Sophie R Weare in 1893 in Iowa, but committed suicide in Seattle in 1906 leaving his wife and two young sons, Lyman J. Gage II (1896-1954) and John Weare Gage (1900-1962).  After Sarah's death, Lyman Gage married Cornelia Lansing, who died childless in 1901. In late 1910s, Gage remarried a third time with Frances Ballou, and the two had a son, Lyman Judson. Frances died in 1943, around 16 years after Gage's death.\n\nIn 1906, Gage indulged his longtime interest in [[metaphysics|metaphysical]] phenomena by purchasing property on and subsequently living at [[Lomaland]], a [[Theosophy (Blavatskian)|Theosophist]] retreat in Southern California. Though this came as something of a shock to the American public, those who knew him privately were not surprised, as Gage had previously studied [[spiritualism]], [[astrology]], and prophesied the death of his own brother through a \"[[psychic]] flash\".<ref>[https://www.loc.gov/chroniclingamerica/lccn/sn84026749/1906-07-15/ed-1/seq-48 Chronicling America - The Library of Congress<!-- bot-generated title -->] at www.loc.gov</ref>\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n{{Commons category}}\n{{wikisource author}}\n*{{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Gage, Lyman Judson}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{U.S. Cabinet official box\n| before= [[John Griffin Carlisle|John G. Carlisle]]\n| after= [[L. M. Shaw|Leslie M. Shaw]]\n| years= March 6, 1897 \u2013 January 31, 1902\n| president= [[William McKinley]], [[Theodore Roosevelt]]\n| department= Secretary of the Treasury}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{USSecTreas}}\n{{McKinley cabinet}}\n{{T Roosevelt cabinet}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gage, Lyman, J.}}\n[[Category:1836 births]]\n[[Category:1927 deaths]]\n[[Category:New York (state) Republicans]]\n[[Category:Burials at Rosehill Cemetery]]\n[[Category:United States Secretaries of the Treasury]]\n[[Category:Theodore Roosevelt administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:20th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:McKinley administration cabinet members]]\n[[Category:19th-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Politicians from Rome, New York]]\n[[Category:California Republicans]]\n", "name_user": "KC Roosters", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adding localshort description: \"American financier and 42nd Secretary of the Treasury\", overriding Wikidata description \"American financier and Secretary of the Treasury\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lyman_J._Gage"}
{"title_page": "Pedigree Petfoods", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2010}}\n{{Globalize|article|United Kingdom|2name=the United Kingdom|date=August 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name = Pedigree Petfoods\n|logo = Pedigree Logo.jpg\n|logo_size = 250px\n|type = \n|company_slogan =\n|foundation = {{start date and age|1957}} (as Chappy)<br>[[Leicestershire]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|U.K.]]\n|hq_location_city = [[McLean, Virginia|McLean]], [[Virginia]]\n|hq_location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n|key_people =\n|parent = [[Mars, Incorporated]]\n|num_employees = 1,200 (estimated)\n|industry = Animal food manufacturing\n|homepage = [http://www.pedigree.com Pedigree Petfoods]\n}}\n\n'''Pedigree Petfoods''' is a subsidiary of the American group [[Mars, Incorporated]] specializing in [[pet food]], with factories in England at Melton Mowbray and Birstall, Leeds; and offices at [[McLean, Virginia]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Manchester===\nIn 1934, Mars Limited, a division of the large American confectionery company, that had been based in [[Slough]] since 1932, acquired Chappel Brothers in [[Manchester]]. This company took low-quality meat and canned it as dog food, branded as \"Chappie\".<ref name=\"Hudson\">Hudson, Kenneth: Industrial history from the air, Cambridge University Press 1984</ref>\n\n===Melton Mowbray===\nIn 1951, annual sales reached \u00a31m, and the company moved to Melton Mowbray, using a former sewing-thread mill previously used by [[Patons and Baldwins]]. In 1953, the company operated seven days a week, twenty four hours a day on a shift system.<ref name=\"Hudson\"/> A continuous sterilisation process was introduced instead of batch processing.\n\nNew dog food brands Pal and Lassie were introduced during the 1950s.<ref name=\"Mars\">[http://www.mars.com/uk/en/who-we-are/our-history/mars-petcare.aspx Mars Petcare] Mars United Kingdom (retrieved 17 Oct 2011)</ref> Due to making more than the Chappie product, the company name changed to Petfoods Ltd in 1956. In 1972, this became Pedigree Petfoods Ltd.\n\nA new factory on Shrewsbury Avenue in Woodston, Peterborough opened in October 1974 which originally produced semi-moist products such as Bounce. In March 1975, it became the Pedigree Petfoods division of Mars Ltd. \n\nDuring the 1970s, around 2,500 workers were at Melton and 200 at Peterborough and produced around 400,000 tonnes of animal food a year and virtually doubled production. The raw materials came from the Oakleigh Manufacturing company in [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]]. Around 3 million cans were used per day at the Melton plant; cans were delivered every 30 minutes, to limit storage space, from the Metal Box company (which became [[Novar plc]]). At this time, Whiskas was the company's biggest product by sales closely followed by Pedigree Chum, although more in volume was sold of Pedigree Chum. Whiskas sold four times as much as Kitekat, although only half as much was spent on advertising Kitekat as Whiskas.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nTowards the late 1980s and in the 1990s, the company came under much more competition from what became [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare]].\n\nA new \u00a322m pouch production line opened in November 2007.\n\nThe company is a member of the Pet Food Manufacturers' Association.\n\n===Mars Inc.===\nIn 1968, Mars took over Kal Kan Foods of [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mars.com/about/history|title=Our History|publisher=[[Mars, Incorporated]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Kal Kan Foods changed the name of its dog food to Pedigree, the name Mars used to sell dog food outside the United States. The cat food continued to be called Kal Kan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-08-12-8801220385-story.html|title=Kal Kan Getting a New Pedigree|last=Lazarus|first=George|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=August 12, 1988|\naccessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Kal-Kan was the top-selling dog food brand but was going downhill. In the United States, its Pedigree Select brand became Cesar, used in Europe and Asia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://adage.com/article/news/mars-kal-kan-rebranding-pedigree-select-cesar-marketer-brings-asia-europe-u-s/65512|title=Mars' Kal-Kan Rebranding Pedigree Select As Cesar: Marketer Brings Name from Asia, Europe to U.S.|last=Pollack|first=Judann|work=[[Advertising Age]]|date=June 15, 1998|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPedigree is now a subsidiary of [[Mars, Incorporated]]. The English division of Mars Inc. has been called Masterfoods since January 2002, until it was split into four separate entities in 2007: Mars Petcare UK, Mars Complementary Petcare UK, Mars Chocolate UK and Mars Food UK.\n\n==Marketing==\n[[File:Dog Food.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Selection of Pedigree dog food]]\nThe company makes the market leaders Pedigree (dog food) and [[Whiskas]] (cat food), as well as Kitekat (cat food) and Pal (dog food). The slogan used for many years for Pedigree dog food is \"Top breeders recommend it because it's solid nourishment\"<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=72R_SGACVLYC&pg=PT107&lpg=PT107&dq=%22because+it%27s+solid+nourishment%22&source=bl&ots=sTX01gxLO7&sig=ACfU3U3XQUKB1YhmfrtKU16wGIauUJKYkg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbg-7n5t_jAhUKQUEAHefxDr4Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22because%20it's%20solid%20nourishment%22&f=false  Anger Management For Beginners by Giles Coren, Hodder & Stoughton 2010 Chapter 48 Processed Ham.]</ref> with a current slogan of \"We're for dogs\". For Whiskas the old slogan was \"8 out of 10 owners say their cat prefers it\" and for Pal it is \"Prolongs Active Life\".\n\nIn [[Australia]], the Pal dog food brand was progressively replaced by the Pedigree logo during the 1980s-2000s.\n\nIn the [[United States]], the original slogan for the Pedigree brand was \"Recommended by top breeders\". It was replaced in 2007 by \"Dogs rule\".\n\n==The Pedigree Foundation==\nIn the United States, The Pedigree Foundation is a [[philanthropic organization]] dedicated to helping shelter dogs find permanent homes. The foundation, created in 2008, provides grants to [[501(c)(3)]] dog shelters and breed rescue organizations, and help dog lovers adopt, volunteer, and make donations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pedigreefoundation.org | title = Pedigree Foundation}}</ref> According to the foundation's [[FAQ]] site, it has raised more than $4 million to date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pedigreefoundation.org/faqs.aspx | title = Pedigree Foundation FAQ}}</ref> In 2008, it distributed more than $1.1 million in grant money to more than 500 [[Animal shelter|shelters]] and breed rescues. Use of awarded grant money by qualified recipients is virtually unrestricted, but is most often used for shelter improvements or [[veterinary]] care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pedigreefoundation.org/PED_Annual_Report_Final.pdf | title = Pedigree Foundation 2008 Annual Report}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Whiskas]]\n* [[Mars, Incorporated]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pedigree.com Pedigree Dog Foods]\n* [http://uk.pedigree.com Pedigree Petfoods UK]\n* [http://www.mars.co.uk Mars UK]\n* [http://www.pedigree.com Pedigree main site]\n\n{{Mars global brands}}\n\n[[Category:Cat food brands]]\n[[Category:Dog food brands]]\n[[Category:Mars brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in McLean, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=March 2010}}\n{{Globalize|article|United Kingdom|2name=the United Kingdom|date=August 2017}}\n}}\n{{Infobox company\n|name = Pedigree Petfoods\n|logo = Pedigree Logo.jpg\n|logo_size = 250px\n|type = \n|company_slogan =\n|foundation = {{start date and age|1957}} (as Chappy)<br>[[Leicestershire]], [[England]], [[United Kingdom|U.K.]]\n|hq_location_city = [[McLean, Virginia|McLean]], [[Virginia]]\n|hq_location_country = [[United States|U.S.]]\n|key_people =\n|parent = [[Mars, Incorporated]]\n|num_employees = 1,200 (estimated)\n|industry = Animal food manufacturing\n|homepage = [http://www.pedigree.com Pedigree Petfoods]\n}}\n\n'''Pedigree Petfoods''' is a subsidiary of the American group [[Mars, Incorporated]] specializing in [[pet food]], with factories in England at Melton Mowbray and Birstall, Leeds; and offices at [[McLean, Virginia]].\n\n==History==\n\n===Manchester===\nIn 1934, Mars Limited, a division of the large American confectionery company, that had been based in [[Slough]] since 1932, acquired Chappel Brothers in [[Manchester]]. This company took low-quality meat and canned it as dog food, branded as \"Chappie\".<ref name=\"Hudson\">Hudson, Kenneth: Industrial history from the air, Cambridge University Press 1984</ref>\n\n===Melton Mowbray===\nIn 1951, annual sales reached \u00a31m, and the company moved to Melton Mowbray, using a former sewing-thread mill previously used by [[Patons and Baldwins]]. In 1953, the company operated seven days a week, twenty four hours a day on a shift system.<ref name=\"Hudson\"/> A continuous sterilisation process was introduced instead of batch processing.\n\nNew dog food brands Pal and Lassie were introduced during the 1950s.<ref name=\"Mars\">[http://www.mars.com/uk/en/who-we-are/our-history/mars-petcare.aspx Mars Petcare] Mars United Kingdom (retrieved 17 Oct 2011)</ref> Due to making more than the Chappie product, the company name changed to Petfoods Ltd in 1956. In 1972, this became Pedigree Petfoods Ltd.\n\nA new factory on Shrewsbury Avenue in Woodston, Peterborough opened in October 1974 which originally produced semi-moist products such as Bounce. In March 1975, it became the Pedigree Petfoods division of Mars Ltd. \n\nDuring the 1970s, around 2,500 workers were at Melton and 200 at Peterborough and produced around 400,000 tonnes of animal food a year and virtually doubled production. The raw materials came from the Oakleigh Manufacturing company in [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]]. Around 3 million cans were used per day at the Melton plant; cans were delivered every 30 minutes, to limit storage space, from the Metal Box company (which became [[Novar plc]]). At this time, Whiskas was the company's biggest product by sales closely followed by Pedigree Chum, although more in volume was sold of Pedigree Chum. Whiskas sold four times as much as Kitekat, although only half as much was spent on advertising Kitekat as Whiskas.{{Citation needed|date=October 2011}}\n\nTowards the late 1980s and in the 1990s, the company came under much more competition from what became [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare]].\n\nA new \u00a322m pouch production line opened in November 2007.\n\nThe company is a member of the Pet Food Manufacturers' Association.\n\n===Mars Inc.===\nIn 1968, Mars took over Kal Kan Foods of [[Los Angeles]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mars.com/about/history|title=Our History|publisher=[[Mars, Incorporated]]|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1988, Kal Kan Foods changed the name of its dog food to Pedigree, the name Mars used to sell dog food outside the United States. The cat food continued to be called Kal Kan.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/news/ct-xpm-1988-08-12-8801220385-story.html|title=Kal Kan Getting a New Pedigree|last=Lazarus|first=George|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|date=August 12, 1988|\naccessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 1998, Kal-Kan was the top-selling dog food brand but was going downhill. In the United States, its Pedigree Select brand became Cesar, used in Europe and Asia.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://adage.com/article/news/mars-kal-kan-rebranding-pedigree-select-cesar-marketer-brings-asia-europe-u-s/65512|title=Mars' Kal-Kan Rebranding Pedigree Select As Cesar: Marketer Brings Name from Asia, Europe to U.S.|last=Pollack|first=Judann|work=[[Advertising Age]]|date=June 15, 1998|accessdate=April 17, 2019}}</ref>\n\nPedigree is now a subsidiary of [[Mars, Incorporated]]. The English division of Mars Inc. has been called Masterfoods since January 2002, until it was split into four separate entities in 2007: Mars Petcare UK, Mars Complementary Petcare UK, Mars Chocolate UK and Mars Food UK.\n\n==Marketing==\n[[File:Dog Food.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Selection of Pedigree dog food]]\nThe company makes the market leaders Pedigree (dog food) and [[Whiskas]] (cat food), as well as Kitekat (cat food) and Pal (dog food). The slogan used for many years for Pedigree dog food is \"Top breeders recommend it because it's solid nourishment\"<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=72R_SGACVLYC&pg=PT107&lpg=PT107&dq=%22because+it%27s+solid+nourishment%22&source=bl&ots=sTX01gxLO7&sig=ACfU3U3XQUKB1YhmfrtKU16wGIauUJKYkg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjbg-7n5t_jAhUKQUEAHefxDr4Q6AEwAXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22because%20it's%20solid%20nourishment%22&f=false  Anger Management For Beginners by Giles Coren, Hodder & Stoughton 2010 Chapter 48 Processed Ham.]</ref> with a current slogan of \"We're for dogs\". For Whiskas the old slogan was \"8 out of 10 owners say their cat prefers it\" and for Pal it is \"Prolongs Active Life\".\n\nIn [[Australia]], the Pal dog food brand was progressively replaced by the Pedigree logo during the 1980s-2000s.\n\nIn the [[United States]], the original slogan for the Pedigree brand was \"Recommended by top breeders\". It was replaced in 2007 by \"Dogs rule\".\n\n==The Pedigree Foundation==\nIn the United States, The Pedigree Foundation is a [[philanthropic organization]] dedicated to helping shelter dogs find permanent homes. The foundation, created in 2008, provides grants to [[501(c)(3)]] dog shelters and breed rescue organizations, and help dog lovers adopt, volunteer, and make donations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pedigreefoundation.org | title = Pedigree Foundation}}</ref> According to the foundation's [[FAQ]] site, it has raised more than $4 million to date.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pedigreefoundation.org/faqs.aspx | title = Pedigree Foundation FAQ}}</ref> In 2008, it distributed more than $1.1 million in grant money to more than 500 [[Animal shelter|shelters]] and breed rescues. Use of awarded grant money by qualified recipients is virtually unrestricted, but is most often used for shelter improvements or [[veterinary]] care.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pedigreefoundation.org/PED_Annual_Report_Final.pdf | title = Pedigree Foundation 2008 Annual Report}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[Whiskas]]\n* [[Mars, Incorporated]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.pedigree.com Pedigree Dog Foods]\n* [http://uk.pedigree.com Pedigree Petfoods UK]\n* [http://www.mars.co.uk Mars UK]\n* [http://www.pedigree.com Pedigree main site]\n\n{{Mars global brands}}\n\n[[Category:Animal food manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Pet food brands]]\n[[Category:Cat food brands]]\n[[Category:Dog food brands]]\n[[Category:Mars brands]]\n[[Category:Companies based in McLean, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "GentlemanGhost", "label": "safe", "comment": "Articles generally should not be in both a category and a sub-category, seeWP:SUBCAT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pedigree_Petfoods"}
{"title_page": "Li Pyong-nam", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Li Pyong-nam\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|office       = Minister of Public Health\n|order        = \n|term_start   = \n|term_end     = \n|deputy       = \n|1blankname   = \n|1namedata    = \n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   =  {{birth date|1903|12|9|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Cheonan]], [[South Chungcheong Province]], [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese Korea]]\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1972|02|18|1903|12|9|mf=y}}\n|death_place  = \n|death_cause = \n|religion     = \n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|branch       = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank         =  \n|commands     = \n|battles      = \n|education    = [[Kyunggi High School]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Keij\u014d Imperial University]]\n|awards      = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\n'''Li Pyong-nam ({{lang-ko|\ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8}})''' (Born December 9, 1903 - died February 18, 1977) was a [[pediatrician]] during the [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese colonial rule]] of [[Korea]] and later a [[politician]] and medical scientist in the [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]. He served as a delegate in the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], North Korea's [[unicameralism|unicameral]] [[parliament]] and also as [[Ministry of Public Health (North Korea)|Minister of Public Health]], in the [[Cabinet of North Korea]] as well as the Chairman of the Central Committee of the [[Korean Red Cross]].<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=21457 \ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8\uc528\uac00 \ubd81\ud55c \ucd08\ub300 \ubcf4\uac74\uc0c1 \ub41c \uc0ac\uc5f0]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Cheonan]], [[South Chungcheong Province]] in 1903.<ref>[http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0073447 \uc774\ubcd1\ub0a8]</ref> During the Japanese colonial rule, after graduating from [[Kyunggi High School]], he graduated from the Faculty of Medicine at [[Keij\u014d Imperial University]], and was a professor there.\n\nAfter [[Surrender of Japan|liberation of Korea]] in 1945, he participated in the founding of the Korean Pediatric Science Society in September. In October of that year, with the recommendation of Myung Joo-wan, he became a professor of pediatrics at Seoul National University College of Medicine which lacked professors. He served as vice-chairman of the Seoul Metropolitan Medical Association, and chairman of the Health Policy Committee of the Namjosun Health Federation, but was arrested twice for joining a leftist group. From January 1946, when the movement against trusteeship became a social controversy, university professors decided not to intervene in political affairs, led by Yoon Il-sun at the time, but Lee Byung-nam became a civilian health expert on the left wing.<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=21457 \ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8\uc528\uac00 \ubd81\ud55c \ucd08\ub300 \ubcf4\uac74\uc0c1 \ub41c \uc0ac\uc5f0]</ref>\n\nWhile serving as a professor of Pediatrics at [[Seoul National University College of Medicine]], he was dismissed for participating in the leftist struggle in 1947, and was reopened in Jongno. In 1948, they supported the North-South negotiations, and in April of that year, they visited Pyongyang to participate in the North-South negotiations, and then settled without encountering them.\n\nIn August of that year, he [[1948 North Korean parliamentary election|was elected]] as deputy to the the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], and on September 9, after the Democratic People's Republic of Korea was [[Day of the Foundation of the Republic|formally established]], he was appointed as it's first [[Ministry of Public Health (North Korea)|Minister of Public Health]] in the [[Cabinet of North Korea]] led by [[Premier of North Korea|Premier]] [[Kim Il-sung]]. He temporarily retired in December of that year, and then became a Health Minister again in September 1949.<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=21457 \ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8\uc528\uac00 \ubd81\ud55c \ucd08\ub300 \ubcf4\uac74\uc0c1 \ub41c \uc0ac\uc5f0]</ref> In 1955, he became the Health Minister of North Korea again and was appointed chairman of the Central Committee of the [[Korean Red Cross]] that year. On September 20, 1957, he was appointed again to the Minister of Health, and once again on July 6th, 1959. In 1960, he became Vice-Chairman of the [[Medical Science Academy of North Korea]] and served until his death.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Korean pediatricians]]\n[[Category:Korean communists]]\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:North Korean politicians]]\n\n[[ko:\ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Li Pyong-nam\n|image        = \n|caption      = \n|office       = Minister of Public Health\n|order        = \n|term_start   = \n|term_end     = \n|deputy       = \n|1blankname   = \n|1namedata    = \n|predecessor  = \n|successor    = \n|birth_name   = \n|birth_date   =  {{birth date|1903|12|9|mf=y}}\n|birth_place  = [[Cheonan]], [[South Chungcheong Province]], [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese Korea]]\n|death_date   = {{death date and age|1972|02|18|1903|12|9|mf=y}}\n|death_place  = \n|death_cause = \n|religion     = \n|nickname     = \n|allegiance   = {{flag|North Korea}}\n|branch       = \n|serviceyears = \n|rank         =  \n|commands     = \n|battles      = \n|education    = [[Kyunggi High School]]\n|alma_mater   = [[Keij\u014d Imperial University]]\n|awards      = \n|party        = [[Workers' Party of Korea]]\n}}\n'''Li Pyong-nam ({{lang-ko|\ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8}})''' (Born December 9, 1903 - died February 18, 1977) was a [[pediatrician]] during the [[Korea under Japanese rule|Japanese colonial rule]] of [[Korea]] and later a [[politician]] and medical scientist in the [[North Korea|Democratic People's Republic of Korea]]. He served as a delegate in the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], North Korea's [[unicameralism|unicameral]] [[parliament]] and also as [[Ministry of Public Health (North Korea)|Minister of Public Health]], in the [[Cabinet of North Korea]] as well as the Chairman of the Central Committee of the [[Korean Red Cross]].<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=21457 \ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8\uc528\uac00 \ubd81\ud55c \ucd08\ub300 \ubcf4\uac74\uc0c1 \ub41c \uc0ac\uc5f0]</ref>\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Cheonan]], [[South Chungcheong Province]] in 1903.<ref>[http://encykorea.aks.ac.kr/Contents/Item/E0073447 \uc774\ubcd1\ub0a8]</ref> During the Japanese colonial rule, after graduating from [[Kyunggi High School]], he graduated from the Faculty of Medicine at [[Keij\u014d Imperial University]], and was a professor there.\n\nAfter [[Surrender of Japan|liberation of Korea]] in 1945, he participated in the founding of the Korean Pediatric Science Society in September. In October of that year, with the recommendation of Myung Joo-wan, he became a professor of pediatrics at Seoul National University College of Medicine which lacked professors. He served as vice-chairman of the Seoul Metropolitan Medical Association, and chairman of the Health Policy Committee of the Namjosun Health Federation, but was arrested twice for joining a leftist group. From January 1946, when the movement against trusteeship became a social controversy, university professors decided not to intervene in political affairs, led by Yoon Il-sun at the time, but Lee Byung-nam became a civilian health expert on the left wing.<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=21457 \ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8\uc528\uac00 \ubd81\ud55c \ucd08\ub300 \ubcf4\uac74\uc0c1 \ub41c \uc0ac\uc5f0]</ref>\n\nWhile serving as a professor of Pediatrics at [[Seoul National University College of Medicine]], he was dismissed for participating in the leftist struggle in 1947, and was reopened in Jongno. In 1948, they supported the North-South negotiations, and in April of that year, they visited Pyongyang to participate in the North-South negotiations, and then settled without encountering them.\n\nIn August of that year, he [[1948 North Korean parliamentary election|was elected]] as deputy to the the [[Supreme People's Assembly]], and on September 9, after the Democratic People's Republic of Korea was [[Day of the Foundation of the Republic|formally established]], he was appointed as it's first [[Ministry of Public Health (North Korea)|Minister of Public Health]] in the [[Cabinet of Morth Korea]] led by [[Premier of North Korea|Premier]] [[Kim Il-sung]]. He temporarily retired in December of that year, and then became a Health Minister again in September 1949.<ref>[http://www.tongilnews.com/news/articleView.html?idxno=21457 \ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8\uc528\uac00 \ubd81\ud55c \ucd08\ub300 \ubcf4\uac74\uc0c1 \ub41c \uc0ac\uc5f0]</ref> In 1955, he became the Health Minister of North Korea again and was appointed chairman of the Central Committee of the [[Korean Red Cross]] that year. On September 20, 1957, he was appointed again to the Minister of Health, and once again on July 6th, 1959. In 1960, he became Vice-Chairman of the [[Medical Science Academy of North Korea]] and served until his death.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Government ministers of North Korea]]\n[[Category:Workers' Party of Korea politicians]]\n[[Category:Korean pediatricians]]\n[[Category:Korean communists]]\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1972 deaths]]\n[[Category:North Korean politicians]]\n\n[[ko:\ub9ac\ubcd1\ub0a8]]\n", "name_user": "Rakoon", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Li_Pyong-nam"}
{"title_page": "Peg Broadbent", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Peg Broadbent|timestamp=20200404100447|year=2020|month=April|day=4|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Peg Broadbent|date=4 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|American executive}}\n'''Peregrine Broadbent''' (1964 \u2013 March 29, 2020) was an English-American executive who was the [[chief financial officer]] (CFO) of the [[Jefferies Group]] from 2007 till his death.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-29/jefferies-group-cfo-dies-from-coronavirus-complications |title=Jefferies Group CFO Dies From Coronavirus Complications |first1=Jennifer |last1=Surane |first2=Hailey |last2=Waller |website=bloomberg.com |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBroadbent, a native of the United Kingdom, grew up in [[London]] and the southwest England county of [[Dorset]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ezequielminaya/2020/03/30/wall-street-executive-succumbs-to-coronavirus-complications/#43d280bc2e77 |title=Wall Street Executive Succumbs To Coronavirus Complications |first=Ezequiel |last=Minaya |website=forbes.com |date=March 30, 2020 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nBroadbent earned an [[BSc]] accounting degree from the [[University of Exeter]].<ref name=\"ft.com\">https://www.ft.com/content/0047fb07-0edd-403f-b1c6-8b2c290544ff</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBroadbent started his career as an accountant at Coopers & Lybrand, a predecessor of the firm [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]].<ref name=\"ft.com\"/> Later, he joined [[Morgan Stanley]] in 1991 where he served for 16 years till 2007.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/jefferies-cfo/jefferies-hires-morgan-stanley-exec-as-cfo-idUSWNAS614320071011 |title = Jefferies hires Morgan Stanley exec as CFO|newspaper = Reuters|date = 11 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/senior-wall-street-executive-dies-of-coronavirus-11585520570 |title=Senior Wall Street Executive Dies of Coronavirus |first=Liz |last=Hoffman |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Broadbent joined Jefferies and remained chief finance officer till his death. During Broadbent's tenure, he is known for helping to double the size of the company.<ref name=\"wsj.com\"/><ref name=\"fnlondon_broadbent2020\"/>\n\nOn March 29, 2020, Broadbent died at the age of 56 due to [[COVID-19]] complications.<ref name=\"fnlondon_broadbent2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fnlondon.com/amp/articles/jefferies-cfo-peg-broadbent-dies-after-contracting-coronavirus-20200329 |title=Jefferies CFO Peg Broadbent dies after contracting coronavirus |website=fnlondon.com |first=Shawn |last=Langlois |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=auto/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broadbent, Peregrine}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:People from Dorset]]\n\n\n{{US-business-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=Peg Broadbent|timestamp=20200404100447|year=2020|month=April|day=4|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=Peg Broadbent|date=4 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{short description|American executive}}\n'''Peregrine Broadbent''' (1964 \u2013 March 29, 2020) was an English-American executive who was the [[chief financial officer]] (CFO) of the [[Jefferies Group]] from 2007 till his death.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-29/jefferies-group-cfo-dies-from-coronavirus-complications |title=Jefferies Group CFO Dies From Coronavirus Complications |first1=Jennifer |last1=Surane |first2=Hailey |last2=Waller |website=bloomberg.com |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Early life and education ==\nBroadbent, a native of the United Kingdom, grew up in [[London]] and the southwest England county of [[Dorset]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/ezequielminaya/2020/03/30/wall-street-executive-succumbs-to-coronavirus-complications/#43d280bc2e77 |title=Wall Street Executive Succumbs To Coronavirus Complications |first=Ezequiel |last=Minaya |website=forbes.com |date=March 30, 2020 |accessdate=March 30, 2020}}</ref> \n\nBroadbent earned an [[BSc]] accounting degree from the [[University of Exeter]].<ref name=\"ft.com\">https://www.ft.com/content/0047fb07-0edd-403f-b1c6-8b2c290544ff</ref>\n\n== Career ==\nBroadbent started his career as an accountant at Coopers & Lybrand, a predecessor of the firm [[PricewaterhouseCoopers]].<ref name=\"ft.com\"/> Later, he joined [[Morgan Stanley]] in 1991 where he served for 16 years till 2007.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/jefferies-cfo/jefferies-hires-morgan-stanley-exec-as-cfo-idUSWNAS614320071011 |title = Jefferies hires Morgan Stanley exec as CFO|newspaper = Reuters|date = 11 October 2007}}</ref><ref name=\"wsj.com\">{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/senior-wall-street-executive-dies-of-coronavirus-11585520570 |title=Senior Wall Street Executive Dies of Coronavirus |first=Liz |last=Hoffman |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref> \n\nIn 2007, Broadbent joined Jefferies and remained chief finance officer till his death. During Broadbent's tenure, he is known for helping to double the size of the company.<ref name=\"wsj.com\"/><ref name=\"fnlondon_broadbent2020\"/>\n\nOn March 29, 2020, Broadbent died at the age of 56 due to [[COVID-2019]] complications.<ref name=\"fnlondon_broadbent2020\">{{cite web |url=https://www.fnlondon.com/amp/articles/jefferies-cfo-peg-broadbent-dies-after-contracting-coronavirus-20200329 |title=Jefferies CFO Peg Broadbent dies after contracting coronavirus |website=fnlondon.com |first=Shawn |last=Langlois |date=March 29, 2020 |accessdate=April 6, 2020}}</ref><ref name=auto/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Broadbent, Peregrine}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Deaths from the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American financiers]]\n[[Category:American business executives]]\n[[Category:English emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Exeter]]\n[[Category:20th-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:21st-century American businesspeople]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople from London]]\n[[Category:People from Dorset]]\n\n\n{{US-business-bio-1960s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Beemer69", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Peg_Broadbent"}
{"title_page": "Genshin Impact", "text_new": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| italic title = \n| title = Genshin Impact\n| image = Genshin_Logo.png\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = miHoYo\n| publisher = \n| series = \n| engine = Unity\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = Spring 2020\n| genre = [[Action role-playing video game|Action role-playing]]\n| modes = \n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| writer = \n| composer = \n| cabinet = \n| arcade system = \n| cpu = \n| sound = \n| display = \n}}\n'''Genshin Impact''' is an upcoming [[open-world]] [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing video game]] developed by miHoYo. It is the second game from miHoYo to feature original IP (the first being Gun GirlZ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mihayo.com/game.html|title=\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38-TECH OTAKUS SAVE THE WORLD|website=www.mihayo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Genshin Impact'' was announced in June 2019, with a release target of spring 2020, on both Windows and iOS - the reveal trailer showed an open world heavily inspired by ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'' in terms of presentation and gameplay. A [[beta test]] was to be run at the end of June.<ref>{{citation| url = https://gamerant.com/genshin-impact-game-zelda/ | title = Zelda-Inspired Open World Action Game 'Genshin Impact' Announced | first = Rory | last = Young | date = 8 June 2019 | work = gamerant.com }}</ref><ref>{{citation|  url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/6/21/18700922/genshin-impact-gameplay-beta-breath-of-the-wild-clone-botw | title = That Breath of the Wild anime \u2018clone\u2019 actually looks impressive | first = Patricia | last = Herndandez | date = 21 June 2019 | work = www.polygon.com }}</ref>\n\nAt Sony's ChinaJoy 2019 event the game was announced as also being published for [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{citation| url = https://gematsu.com/2019/08/genshin-impact-coming-to-ps4-in-2020 | title = Genshin Impact coming to PS4 in 2020 | first = Sal | last = Romano | date = 1 Aug 2019 | work = gematsu.com }}</ref> A [[Nintendo Switch]] version was announced on January 13, 2020 via press release.\n\n==Localisation==\nDespite being localised in 12 different languages (13 when distinguishing traditional and simplified Chinese), the localisation effort on ''Genshin Impact'' is more pronounced in Chinese, Japanese and Korean as the dialogues are all voiced into those 3 languages. Possibly because of the international reach of Japanese media and the fact that miHoYo was founded by Japanese anime fans, only Japanese voices are proposed to languages other than those 3.\n\nMoreover, ''Genshin Impact'' takes a different title in Chinese, Japanese and Korean, simply shorten to the first word of the international title i.e. ''Yu\u00e1nsh\u00e9n'' \u539f\u795e in Chinese, ''Genshin'' \u539f\u795e in Japanese and ''Wonsin'' \uc6d0\uc2e0 in Korean. The different pronouciations simply reflect the local way of pronouncing the original Chinese title, which literally means ''Primordial Gods''.\n\n== Setting ==\nIn a world called Teyvat, certain individuals chosen by the gods are given a Vision \u2014 magical gemstones that give their bearers the ability to control an element. The player starts out as a Traveler of unknown origin who is searching for a lost sibling. The player can choose between a male or female version of the Traveler. As the adventure progresses, the player controls several other characters met by the Traveler on their journey, each with unique personalities and special abilities, as they undertake quests to understand the truth about the primordial gods of this world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe game features an open-world map, which the player explores by walking, climbing, swimming and gliding as necessary. Many objects and places of significance are spread throughout the map.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/detail.php?sn=180824|title=\u300a\u5d29\u58de 3rd\u300b\u958b\u767c\u5546\u958b\u653e\u4e16\u754c\u5192\u96aa\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u66dd\u5149 \u540c\u6b65\u516c\u958b\u9996\u652f\u9810\u544a\u5f71\u7247|website=\u5df4\u54c8\u59c6\u7279\u96fb\u73a9\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7ad9|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Players can control up to four of their characters at any one time. By completing quests to advance the story, the player is able to unlock a total of 30 playable characters.\n\nEach character has two unique combat skills: a normal and a special skill. The normal skill can be used at any time except for the cooldown period immediately after use, while the special skill has an energy cost, requiring the user to amass sufficient elemental energy first.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_2.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Genshinimpact/|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nCooking is another significant aspect of Genshin Impact's gameplay. Players gather many resources in the course of their adventure, some of which can be turned into dishes via cooking. Some dishes regenerate characters' health, while others boost attack or defensive abilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_3.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nmiHoYo announced work on a new project using the Unity development platform at the end of January 2017, three months after the initial release of Honkai Impact 3rd. The company stated its intention for the new project was to strengthen the company's R&D capabilities and produce higher-quality games. The project in question was Genshin Impact.\n\nThe game's developers have cited The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild and the Grand Theft Auto series among their influences. They sought to create a game that was distinct from Honkai Impact 3rd in terms of its quest and combat systems as well as its random events and mode of exploration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/570|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese version of the game features audio dialogue in Chinese, while the Japanese version notably features Japanese audio dialogue by many top Japanese voice artists, including Rie Tanaka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/698|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/1000|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Characters ==\nDuring the [[Tokyo Game Show]] in 2019, miHoYo released a promotional video for the Japanese voice acting in Genshin Impact. The video revealed several of the game's characters and their corresponding voice artists.\n\n'''Traveler (male)''', voiced by [[Shun Horie]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Traveler (female)''', voiced by [[Aoi Y\u016bki]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Jean''', voiced by [[Chiwa Sait\u014d]] (Japanese), the acting Grand Master of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Amber''', voiced by [[Manaka Iwami]] (Japanese), a perky, straightforward girl, who is an Outrider of the Knights of Favonius. Her mastery of the glider has made her a three-time winner of the Gliding Championship in Mondstadt.\n\n'''Lisa''', voiced by [[Rie Tanaka]] (Japanese), an erudite witch much enamored with getting plenty of high-quality sleep, Lisa is the Librarian of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Kaeya''', voiced by [[K\u014dsuke Toriumi]] (Japanese), Jean's most trusted aide in the organization. His quick wit and keen sense of humour has greatly endeared him to the residents of Mondstadt.\n\n'''Barbara''', voiced by [[Akari Kit\u014d]] (Japanese), the Deaconess of the Knights of Favonius and a shining starlet adored by all.\n\n'''Diluc''', voiced by [[Kensh\u014d Ono]] (Japanese), the most well-to-do man in Mondstadt, as can be deduced from his refined and graceful demeanor. At the same time, he believes fiercely in the duty to defend Mondstadt at all costs \u2014 something that makes him a ruthless and terrifying force on the battlefield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/character/mondstadt|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Paimon''', voiced by [[Aoi Koga]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Venti''', voiced by [[Ayumu Murase]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Razor''', voiced by [[K\u014dki Uchiyama]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Xiangling''', voiced by [[Ari Ozawa]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Kamisato Ayaka''', voiced by [[Saori Hayami]] (Japanese)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Press ==\nmiHoYo publishes an official Genshin Impact manga series, which is hosted on sites including Crunchyroll,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/comics/manga/genshin-impact/volumes|title=Genshin Impact on Crunchyroll!|website=Crunchyroll|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Tapas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tapas.io/series/Genshin-Impact|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Tapas|last=Tapas|website=tapas.io|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> and Webtoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webtoons.com/en/challenge/genshin-impact/list?title_no=242646|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.webtoons.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The series started in 2018, before the game itself was published.\n\nmiHoYo discussed Genshin Impact in an interview with Chinese TV station Dragon Television in January 2019. The interview was featured in the station's Primetime News program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cctv.com/2019/01/15/VIDEllNBWIsRNxHQcQESVSSf190115.shtml|title=[\u4e1c\u65b9\u65b0\u95fb]\u4ece\"\u65e0\u4eba\u95ee\u6d25\"\u5230\u5e74\u516520\u4ebf \"85\u540e\"\u521b\u4e1a\u8005\u6253\u9020\u4f18\u8d28\u56fd\u4ea7\u52a8\u6f2bIP_\u65b0\u95fb\u9891\u9053_\u592e\u89c6\u7f51(cctv.com)|website=news.cctv.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nGenshin Impact was first shown to the public in June 2019 at the Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/videos/1057341/genshin-impact-un-melange-de-tales-of-et-breath-of-the-wild.htm|title=Bande-annonce Genshin Impact : un m\u00e9lange de Tales of et Breath of the Wild - E3 2019|website=Jeuxvideo.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first trailer for Genshin Impact was released on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact Announcement Trailer: The Outlander Who Caught The Wind|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMdsrZ1otlA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first closed beta testing for Genshin Impact commenced on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ithome.com/0/427/220.htm|title=\u300a\u5d29\u574f3\u300b\u4e4b\u540e\uff0c\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u5f00\u542f\u6d4b\u8bd5\u9884\u7ea6 - \u7c73\u54c8\u6e38,\u539f\u795e - IT\u4e4b\u5bb6|website=www.ithome.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nAt ChinaJoy 2019, miHoYo announced that Genshin Impact will be made available for the PlayStation 4 console in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Gameplay Trailer {{!}} PS4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1WmmsEXtyE|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nA trailer for Genshin Impact with Japanese audio was shown to audiences at the Tokyo Game Show in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact: Come explore Teyvat with Amber! (Japanese Version)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kuLkPigM8Mg|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nMultiple language versions of the Genshin Impact website went live in September 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genshin.mihoyo.com genshin.mihoyo.com] , official website\n*[https://www.yuanshen.com www.yuanshen.com] , official Chinese website\n\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n[[Category:Upcoming video games scheduled for 2020]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Undisclosed paid|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox video game\n| collapsible = \n| state = \n| italic title = \n| title = Genshin Impact\n| image = Genshin_Logo.png\n| alt = \n| caption = \n| developer = miHoYo\n| publisher = \n| series = \n| engine = Unity\n| platforms = [[PlayStation 4]], [[Microsoft Windows]], [[iOS]], [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[Nintendo Switch]]\n| released = Spring 2020\n| genre = [[Action role-playing video game|Action role-playing]]\n| modes = \n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| writer = \n| composer = \n| cabinet = \n| arcade system = \n| cpu = \n| sound = \n| display = \n}}\n'''Genshin Impact''' is an upcoming [[open-world]] [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing video game]] developed by miHoYo. It is the second game from miHoYo to feature original IP (the first being Gun GirlZ).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mihayo.com/game.html|title=\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38-TECH OTAKUS SAVE THE WORLD|website=www.mihayo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''Genshin Impact'' was announced in June 2019, with a release target of spring 2020, on both Windows and iOS - the reveal trailer showed an open world heavily inspired by ''[[The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild]]'' in terms of presentation and gameplay. A [[beta test]] was to be run at the end of June.<ref>{{citation| url = https://gamerant.com/genshin-impact-game-zelda/ | title = Zelda-Inspired Open World Action Game 'Genshin Impact' Announced | first = Rory | last = Young | date = 8 June 2019 | work = gamerant.com }}</ref><ref>{{citation|  url = https://www.polygon.com/2019/6/21/18700922/genshin-impact-gameplay-beta-breath-of-the-wild-clone-botw | title = That Breath of the Wild anime \u2018clone\u2019 actually looks impressive | first = Patricia | last = Herndandez | date = 21 June 2019 | work = www.polygon.com }}</ref>\n\nAt Sony's ChinaJoy 2019 event the game was announced as also being published for [[PlayStation 4]].<ref>{{citation| url = https://gematsu.com/2019/08/genshin-impact-coming-to-ps4-in-2020 | title = Genshin Impact coming to PS4 in 2020 | first = Sal | last = Romano | date = 1 Aug 2019 | work = gematsu.com }}</ref> A [[Nintendo Switch]] version was announced on January 13, 2020 via press release.\n\n==Localisation==\nDespite being localised in 12 different languages (13 when distinguishing traditional and simplified Chinese), the localisation effort on ''Genshin Impact'' is more pronounced in Chinese, Japanese and Korean as the dialogues are all voiced into those 3 languages. Possibly because of the international reach of Japanese media and the fact that miHoYo was founded by Japanese anime fans, only Japanese voices are proposed to languages other than those 3.\n\nMoreover, ''Genshin Impact'' takes a different title in Chinese, Japanese and Korean, simply shorten to the first word of the international title i.e. ''Yu\u00e1nsh\u00e9n'' \u539f\u795e in Chinese, ''Genshin'' \u539f\u795e in Japanese and ''Wonsin'' \uc6d0\uc2e0 in Korean. The different pronouciations simply reflect the local way of pronouncing the original Chinese title, which literally means ''Primordial Gods''.\n\n== Setting ==\nIn a world called Teyvat, certain individuals chosen by the gods are given a Vision \u2014 magical gemstones that give their bearers the ability to control an element. The player starts out as a Traveler of unknown origin who is searching for a lost sibling. The player can choose between a male or female version of the Traveler. As the adventure progresses, the player controls several other characters met by the Traveler on their journey, each with unique personalities and special abilities, as they undertake quests to understand the truth about the primordial gods of this world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Gameplay ==\nThe game features an open-world map, which the player explores by walking, climbing, swimming and gliding as necessary. Many objects and places of significance are spread throughout the map.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/detail.php?sn=180824|title=\u300a\u5d29\u58de 3rd\u300b\u958b\u767c\u5546\u958b\u653e\u4e16\u754c\u5192\u96aa\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u66dd\u5149 \u540c\u6b65\u516c\u958b\u9996\u652f\u9810\u544a\u5f71\u7247|website=\u5df4\u54c8\u59c6\u7279\u96fb\u73a9\u8cc7\u8a0a\u7ad9|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Players can control up to four of their characters at any one time. By completing quests to advance the story, the player is able to unlock a total of 30 playable characters.\n\nEach character has two unique combat skills: a normal and a special skill. The normal skill can be used at any time except for the cooldown period immediately after use, while the special skill has an energy cost, requiring the user to amass sufficient elemental energy first.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_2.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/Genshinimpact/|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.facebook.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nCooking is another significant aspect of Genshin Impact's gameplay. Players gather many resources in the course of their adventure, some of which can be turned into dishes via cooking. Some dishes regenerate characters' health, while others boost attack or defensive abilities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://shouyou.gamersky.com/review/201906/1196056_3.shtml|title=\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u6d4b\u8bd5\u7248\u8bd5\u73a9\uff1a\u56fd\u4ea7\u624b\u6e38\u79bb3A\u6700\u8fd1\u7684\u4e00\u6b21 _ \u6e38\u6c11\u661f\u7a7a\u624b\u6e38\u9891\u9053|website=shouyou.gamersky.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Development ==\nmiHoYo announced work on a new project using the Unity development platform at the end of January 2017, three months after the initial release of Honkai Impact 3rd. The company stated its intention for the new project was to strengthen the company's R&D capabilities and produce higher-quality games. The project in question was Genshin Impact.\n\nThe game's developers have cited The Legend of Zelda: Breath of the Wild and the Grand Theft Auto series among their influences. They sought to create a game that was distinct from Honkai Impact 3rd in terms of its quest and combat systems as well as its random events and mode of exploration.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/570|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe Chinese version of the game features audio dialogue in Chinese, while the Japanese version notably features Japanese audio dialogue by many top Japanese voice artists, including Rie Tanaka.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/698|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/news/detail/1000|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n== Characters ==\nDuring the [[Tokyo Game Show]] in 2019, miHoYo released a promotional video for the Japanese voice acting in Genshin Impact. The video revealed several of the game's characters and their corresponding voice artists.\n\n'''Traveler (male)''', voiced by [[Shun Horie]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Traveler (female)''', voiced by [[Aoi Y\u016bki]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Jean''', voiced by [[Chiwa Sait\u014d]] (Japanese), the acting Grand Master of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Amber''', voiced by [[Manaka Iwami]] (Japanese), a perky, straightforward girl, who is an Outrider of the Knights of Favonius. Her mastery of the glider has made her a three-time winner of the Gliding Championship in Mondstadt.\n\n'''Lisa''', voiced by [[Rie Tanaka]] (Japanese), an erudite witch much enamored with getting plenty of high-quality sleep, Lisa is the Librarian of the Knights of Favonius.\n\n'''Kaeya''', voiced by [[K\u014dsuke Toriumi]] (Japanese), Jean's most trusted aide in the organization. His quick wit and keen sense of humour has greatly endeared him to the residents of Mondstadt.\n\n'''Barbara''', voiced by [[Akari Kit\u014d]] (Japanese), the Deaconess of the Knights of Favonius and a shining starlet adored by all.\n\n'''Diluc''', voiced by [[Kensh\u014d Ono]] (Japanese), the most well-to-do man in Mondstadt, as can be deduced from his refined and graceful demeanor. At the same time, he believes fiercely in the duty to defend Mondstadt at all costs \u2014 something that makes him a ruthless and terrifying force on the battlefield.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genshin.mihoyo.com/en/character/mondstadt|title=Genshin Impact-Step into a Vast Magical World for Adventure|website=genshin.mihoyo.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Paimon''', voiced by [[Aoi Koga]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Venti''', voiced by [[Ayumu Murase]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Razor''', voiced by [[K\u014dki Uchiyama]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Xiangling''', voiced by [[Ari Ozawa]] (Japanese)\n\n'''Kamisato Ayaka''', voiced by [[Saori Hayami]] (Japanese)<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Press ==\nmiHoYo publishes an official Genshin Impact manga series, which is hosted on sites including Crunchyroll,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.crunchyroll.com/comics/manga/genshin-impact/volumes|title=Genshin Impact on Crunchyroll!|website=Crunchyroll|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> Tapas<ref>{{cite web|url=https://tapas.io/series/Genshin-Impact|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Tapas|last=Tapas|website=tapas.io|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> and Webtoon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.webtoons.com/en/challenge/genshin-impact/list?title_no=242646|title=Genshin Impact|website=www.webtoons.com|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> The series started in 2018, before the game itself was published.\n\nmiHoYo discussed Genshin Impact in an interview with Chinese TV station Dragon Television in January 2019. The interview was featured in the station's Primetime News program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.cctv.com/2019/01/15/VIDEllNBWIsRNxHQcQESVSSf190115.shtml|title=[\u4e1c\u65b9\u65b0\u95fb]\u4ece\"\u65e0\u4eba\u95ee\u6d25\"\u5230\u5e74\u516520\u4ebf \"85\u540e\"\u521b\u4e1a\u8005\u6253\u9020\u4f18\u8d28\u56fd\u4ea7\u52a8\u6f2bIP_\u65b0\u95fb\u9891\u9053_\u592e\u89c6\u7f51(cctv.com)|website=news.cctv.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nGenshin Impact was first shown to the public in June 2019 at the Electronic Entertainment Expo in Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/videos/1057341/genshin-impact-un-melange-de-tales-of-et-breath-of-the-wild.htm|title=Bande-annonce Genshin Impact : un m\u00e9lange de Tales of et Breath of the Wild - E3 2019|website=Jeuxvideo.com|language=fr|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first trailer for Genshin Impact was released on June 8, 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact Announcement Trailer: The Outlander Who Caught The Wind|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=lMdsrZ1otlA|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nThe first closed beta testing for Genshin Impact commenced on June 21, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ithome.com/0/427/220.htm|title=\u300a\u5d29\u574f3\u300b\u4e4b\u540e\uff0c\u7c73\u54c8\u6e38\u65b0\u4f5c\u300a\u539f\u795e\u300b\u5f00\u542f\u6d4b\u8bd5\u9884\u7ea6 - \u7c73\u54c8\u6e38,\u539f\u795e - IT\u4e4b\u5bb6|website=www.ithome.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nAt ChinaJoy 2019, miHoYo announced that Genshin Impact will be made available for the PlayStation 4 console in 2020.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact {{!}} Gameplay Trailer {{!}} PS4|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=S1WmmsEXtyE|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nA trailer for Genshin Impact with Japanese audio was shown to audiences at the Tokyo Game Show in September 2019.<ref>{{cite web|title=Genshin Impact: Come explore Teyvat with Amber! (Japanese Version)|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kuLkPigM8Mg|language=en|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref>\n\nMultiple language versions of the Genshin Impact website went live in September 2019.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genshin.mihoyo.com genshin.mihoyo.com] , official website\n*[https://www.yuanshen.com www.yuanshen.com] , official chinese website\n\n[[Category:PlayStation 4 games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Open world video games]]\n[[Category:Fantasy video games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]