{"title_page": "Faena Hotel Buenos Aires", "text_new": "[[File:Faena Hotel Universe, Puerto Madero.jpg|thumbnail|right|External view of the hotel.]]\nThe '''Faena Hotel Buenos Aires''', formally known as Faena Hotel+Universe, is a [[five-star hotel]] in the [[Puerto Madero]] section of [[Buenos Aires]].<ref>[http://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g312741-d306696-Reviews-Faena_Hotel_Universe-Buenos_Aires_Capital_Federal_District.html Trip Advisor: Faena Hotel + Universe]</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe lot where the hotel sits today was originally purchased in 1902 by [[Bunge y Born]], a leading local [[agribusiness]] firm. They had one of the largest wheat mills in the country, which allowed them to establish ''Molinos R\u00edo de la Plata'' (a leader in the local retail-foods market).<ref name=educ>[http://www.educ.ar/educar/site/educar/kbee:/educar/content/portal-content/taxonomia-recursos/recurso/ec264d95-fe4d-4ca0-91a9-56f79f08e909.recurso/943ae22b-4e52-49f0-97f3-b7ed2ddd0762/soc-poli-6.pdf educ.ar - el caso de Bunge y Born {{in lang|es}}]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe structure measured 25,000 m<sup>2</sup> (270,000&nbsp;ft<sup>2</sup>) in indoor area and was built with bricks imported from [[Manchester]]. The development of a new port further north after 1911 led to the original docklands' obsolescence, however, and by 1998, the shuttered ''El Porte\u00f1o'' building (as the historic mill was known locally) had been slated for demolition.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/1998/07/24/e-04301d.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' (7/24/1998) {{in lang|es}}]</ref>\n\nSaved from the wrecking ball by local cultural preservation associations, the building was purchased by former fashion designer [[Alan Faena]], who, after a US$40 million investment, opened the Faena Hotel in October 2004.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/2004/12/28/conexiones/t-894818.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' {{in lang|es}}]</ref>\n\nFaena, together with interior designer [[Philippe Starck]], developed the structure into a hotel with 88 rooms and residential 80 units. The hotel includes the rustic ''El Mercado'' restaurant, Bistro Sur restaurant, Library Lounge bar, La Cave wine cellar and private dining room, fashion boutique, El Cabaret, and Faena Spa. El Cabaret hosts the number-one tango show in Buenos Aires, \"Rojo Tango\". The hotel forms the core of the larger Faena District in Buenos Aires. Faena worked with [[Norman Foster, Baron Foster of Thames Bank|Norman Foster]] to create the Faena Aleph Residences - [[Foster and Partners]]' first project in Latin America, completed in January 2013.<ref>[http://inhabitat.com/foster-partners-completes-first-project-in-south-america-climate-friendly-faena-aleph-apartments/ \"Foster + Partners Completes First Project in South America: Climate-Friendly Faena Aleph Apartments\"], ''Inhabitat.com''</ref>\n\n==Notable guests==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Madonna (entertainer)|Madonna]]\n* [[Emma Watson]]\n* [[Lady Gaga]]\n* [[Justin Bieber]]\n* [[Sting (musician)|Sting]]\n* [[John Cusack]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The hotel featured in the 2015 film ''[[Focus (2015 film)|Focus]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090228033702/http%3A//www.faenahotelanduniverse.com// Faena Hotel and Universe]\n\n{{coord|34|36|50|S|58|21|42|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faena Hotel+Universe}}\n[[Category:Hotels in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Argentine companies established in 2004]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Faena Hotel Universe, Puerto Madero.jpg|thumbnail|right|External view of the hotel.]]\nThe '''Faena Hotel Buenos Aires''', formally known as Faena Hotel+Universe, is a [[five-star hotel]] in the [[Puerto Madero]] section of [[Buenos Aires]].<ref>[http://www.tripadvisor.com/Hotel_Review-g312741-d306696-Reviews-Faena_Hotel_Universe-Buenos_Aires_Capital_Federal_District.html Trip Advisor: Faena Hotel + Universe]</ref>\n\n==Overview==\nThe lot where the hotel sits today was originally purchased in 1902 by [[Bunge y Born]], a leading local [[agribusiness]] firm. They had one of the largest wheat mills in the country, which allowed them to establish ''Molinos R\u00edo de la Plata'' (a leader in the local retail-foods market).<ref name=educ>[http://www.educ.ar/educar/site/educar/kbee:/educar/content/portal-content/taxonomia-recursos/recurso/ec264d95-fe4d-4ca0-91a9-56f79f08e909.recurso/943ae22b-4e52-49f0-97f3-b7ed2ddd0762/soc-poli-6.pdf educ.ar - el caso de Bunge y Born {{in lang|es}}]{{dead link|date=September 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nThe structure measured 25,000 m<sup>2</sup> (270,000&nbsp;ft<sup>2</sup>) in indoor area and was built with bricks imported from [[Manchester]]. The development of a new port further north after 1911 led to the original docklands' obsolescence, however, and by 1998, the shuttered ''El Porte\u00f1o'' building (as the historic mill was known locally) had been slated for demolition.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/1998/07/24/e-04301d.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' (7/24/1998) {{in lang|es}}]</ref>\n\nSaved from the wrecking ball by local cultural preservation associations, the building was purchased by former fashion designer [[Alan Faena]], who, after a US$40 million investment, opened the Faena Hotel in October 2004.<ref>[http://www.clarin.com/diario/2004/12/28/conexiones/t-894818.htm ''Clar\u00edn'' {{in lang|es}}]</ref>\n\nFaena, together with interior designer [[Philippe Starck]], developed the structure into a hotel with 88 rooms and residential 80 units. The hotel includes the rustic ''El Mercado'' restaurant, Bistro Sur restaurant, Library Lounge bar, La Cave wine cellar and private dining room, fashion boutique, El Cabaret, and Faena Spa. El Cabaret hosts the number-one tango show in Buenos Aires, \"Rojo Tango\". The hotel forms the core of the larger Faena District in Buenos Aires. Faena worked with [[Norman Foster, Baron Foster of Thames Bank|Norman Foster]] to create the Faena Aleph Residences - [[Foster and Partners]]' first project in Latin America, completed in January 2013.<ref>[http://inhabitat.com/foster-partners-completes-first-project-in-south-america-climate-friendly-faena-aleph-apartments/ \"Foster + Partners Completes First Project in South America: Climate-Friendly Faena Aleph Apartments\"], ''Inhabitat.com''</ref>\n\n==Notable guests==\n{{div col|colwidth=20em}}\n* [[Madonna]]\n* [[Emma Watson]]\n* [[Lady Gaga]]\n* [[Justin Bieber]]\n* [[Sting]]\n* [[John Cusack]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==In popular culture==\n* The hotel featured in the 2015 film ''[[Focus (2015 film)|Focus]]''.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n[http://webarchive.loc.gov/all/20090228033702/http%3A//www.faenahotelanduniverse.com// Faena Hotel and Universe]\n\n{{coord|34|36|50|S|58|21|42|W|display=title}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faena Hotel+Universe}}\n[[Category:Hotels in Buenos Aires]]\n[[Category:Hotels established in 2004]]\n[[Category:Argentine companies established in 2004]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Madonna\u2192Madonna (entertainer),Sting\u2192Sting (musician)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Faena_Hotel_Buenos_Aires"}
{"title_page": "Ralston Purina", "text_new": "{{For|the Ralston portion of the now defunct Ralston Purina Company|Ralcorp}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Ralston Purina Company\n| logo = [[Image:Lg checker.svg|centre||160px]]\n| caption = \n| fate = Acquired by [[Nestl\u00e9]]; merged into Nestl\u00e9's pet food business\n| successor = [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1894|01|08}} (as [[Purina Mills]])\n| founder = [[William H. Danforth]]\n| defunct = {{End date|2001|12|12}}\n| location_city = [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]\n| location_country = [[United States|USA]]\n| industry = Food, pet food, animal feeds\n| products = [[Dog food]], [[cat food]], [[animal health]] products, [[breakfast cereal]], [[crisp bread]]\n}}\n\n'''Ralston Purina Company''' was a [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\u2013based American [[Compound feed|animal feed]], food and [[pet food]] company. On December 12, 2001, it [[merger|merged]] with [[Switzerland|Swiss]] food-giant [[Nestl\u00e9|Nestl\u00e9's]] [[Friskies PetCare Company|Friskies]] division to form [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare|Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.purina.com/|title=Purina: Nutritious Dog and Cat Food for Your Pet|website=www.purina.com}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nRalston Purina (originally  Ralston-Purina) traces its roots to 1894, when founder [[William H. Danforth]] established the animal feed company [[Purina Mills]]. Danforth, formed a partnership with George Robinson; William Andrews, entered the business of feeding farm animals by founding the Robinson-Danforth Commission Company. Its predominant brand for each animal was generally referred to as \"Chow\"; hence \"Purina Horse Chow\", \"Purina [[Dog Chow]]\", \"Purina Cat Chow\", \"Purina Rabbit Chow\", \"Purina Pig Chow\", and \"Purina Monkey Chow\".  \n\nLater, the company began producing cereal, which received endorsement by [[Webster Edgerly]], founder of [[Ralstonism]], to market Ralston [[breakfast cereals]]. Edgerly was at the time promoting the consumption of whole-grain cereal. These cereals became so successful that the name of the enterprise was changed in 1902 to the Ralston-Purina Company.<ref name=\"Washington City Paper\">{{Citation\n  | last = Carman\n  | first = Tim\n  | author-link = | last2 =\n  | first2 =\n  | author2-link =\n  | title = Food History Potpourri: Ralston Purina's D.C. Roots\n  | newspaper = Washington City Paper\n  | pages =\n  | date = 2009-04-16\n  | url = http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/youngandhungry/2009/04/16/food-history-potpourri-ralston-purinas-dc-roots/\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-19\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.purina-arabia.com/meet-purina/history|title=History of Ralston Purina|publisher=Purina}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Ralston Purina sold Purina Mills, its US animal feed business, to [[British Petroleum]]. Purina Mills is now owned by [[Land O'Lakes]]. In 1994, the Ralston \"human food\" operations of the Ralston Purina Company were spun off into a new company called [[Ralcorp|Ralcorp Holdings]]. In 1998, Ralston Purina spun off its international animal feed business as Agribrands, which was acquired by [[Cargill]] in 2001.<ref>[http://www.cargill.com/feed/about/history/index.jsp History] at Cargill.com</ref> The animal feed businesses continue to use the Purina and Chow brands, which Purina Mills and Cargill license for use in the US and internationally, respectively.\n\n===Merger with Nestl\u00e9===\nRalston Purina became the subject of an acquisition bid by [[Switzerland|Swiss]]-based [[Nestl\u00e9]], whose [[Friskies]] brand was the other leading US brand of pet food.  Nestl\u00e9 S.A. and Ralston Purina announced in January 2001 a definitive merger agreement.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news\n  | last = Ackman\n  | first = Dan\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Nestle Seals Ralston Deal\n  | newspaper = Forbes\n  | location =\n  | pages = \n  | date = 2001-01-16\n  | url = https://www.forbes.com/2001/01/16/0116dogfood.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-19}}</ref> Under the agreement, Nestl\u00e9 acquired all of Ralston Purina's (NYSE: RAL) outstanding shares for US$33.50 per share in cash. The offer represented a premium of 36% over the closing price on Friday, January 12, 2001. The transaction had an [[enterprise value]] of US$10.3 billion ($10.0 billion equity plus $1.2 billion of net debt, minus $0.9 billion of financial investments).\n\nBoth corporations saw this major strategic transaction as the ideal way to benefit from their combined know-how, complementary strengths, and international presence in the growing pet-care market.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} Several brands of pet food (e.g., \"[[Meow Mix]]\") had to be divested separately to meet [[antitrust]] concerns. Purina brands are now made and marketed by a division of Nestl\u00e9 (Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare) which is still headquartered in St. Louis.\n\nWhile primarily a pet-food company, Ralston Purina also made some other pet-related products, such as [[Tidy Cats]] brand and Yesterday's News [[cat litter]], which is made from recycled newspaper, purchased from [[Edward Lowe Industries]] in 1990. Also, Purina has honoured several Canadian animals every year since 1968 in their Animal Hall of Fame. The latest inductees included a police service dog which \"rushed and subdued an armed robber\".\n\n==Acquisitions and diversifications==\n\nIn 1977, Ralston Purina acquired Missouri Arena Corporation and the [[St. Louis Blues]] [[National Hockey League]] franchise.  During the company's ownership of the team, they changed the name of the [[St. Louis Arena]] to the Checkerdome, reflecting the Ralston Purina logo.  The franchise was sold to Harry Ornest on July 27, 1983.\n\nRalston Purina purchased the [[Energizer Holdings|Eveready Battery Company]] in 1986, owner of the Eveready and Energizer brands. The company was spun off in 2000.\n\nRalston Purina purchased [[Continental Baking Company]], makers of [[Wonder bread]] and [[Hostess (brand)|Hostess cakes]], from [[ITT Corporation|ITT]] in 1984.  Ralston spun off Continental Baking Company, subsequently bought by Irving, Texas\u2013based [[Interstate Bakeries Corporation|Interstate Brands Corporation]] (IBC).\n\nRalston Purina opened test market pizza stores called Checkerboard Pizza in 1986. The format was similar to Domino's and Little Caesars.  They opened the stores in markets such as Moorhead, Minnesota, to test how the Midwestern market would accept the concept.  They did well, but Ralston Purina decided not to enter the pizza franchise business and closed all pilots by late 1987.\n   \nRalston Purina owned and further developed the Keystone ski resort in Colorado.  The \"Checkerboard\" slope for kids and beginners at Keystone still bears their logo.\n\nRalston Purina also owned [[Jack in the Box]] fast food restaurants from 1968 to 1985,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jackintheboxinc.com/company/history|title=Jack In The Box Inc. - Our Company|publisher=}}</ref> along with several high-end restaurants.\n\nRalston Purina owned [[Van Camp Sea Food Company]] from 1963 to 1988, a tuna cannery with Chicken of the Sea as its main product.\n\nRalston Purina owned an animal pharmaceutical company in the 1970s and 1980s.\n\n==Logo==\nRalston Purina's \"checkerboard\" [[trademark]] was introduced in 1902.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stltoday.newspapers.com/image/142210749|title=Ralston Purina Evolved from a Small Store|date=February 16, 1964|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|title=Nestl\u00e9 in the United States: A Celebration of Good Food, Good Life|last=Rodengen|first=Jeffrey|publisher=Write Stuff Enterprises, LLC|year=2016|isbn=9781932022704|location=Fort Lauderdale, FL|pages=101}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Ralston Chronicle, 1894-1994: A Century of Managing Change|last=|first=|publisher=Ralston Purina Company|year=1994|isbn=|location=Saint Louis, MO|pages=i}}</ref> It was inspired by [[William_H._Danforth|William Danforth]]'s childhood memory of a family dressed in clothing made from the same bolt of checkerboard cloth.<ref name=\"Purina History\">{{cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = A Glimpse from the Past to the Present\n  | work =\n  | publisher = Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Produits Nestl\u00e9 S.A., Vevey, Switzerland\n  | date =\n  | url = http://nestlepurinacareers.com/CultureBenefits/PurinaHistory.aspx\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-19}}</ref> The company's headquarters was called Checkerboard Square. Danforth used the design as the visualization of a concept put forth in his book ''I Dare You'', in which he proposed that four key components in life (\"Physical\", \"Mental\", \"Social\", and \"Religious\") need to be in balance, and one area was not to develop at the expense of the others.<ref name=\"I Dare You\">{{cite book\n  | last = Danforth\n  | first = William\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = I Dare You!\n  | publisher = Kessinger Publishing, LLC\n  | date =\n  | location =\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 0-7661-2786-9}}</ref> In 1921, the design inspired the design of feed that was pressed in cubes, called \"checkers\".<ref name=\"Danforth Profile\">{{cite web\n |title=William H. Danforth, Founder \n |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Produits Nestl\u00e9 S.A., Vevey, Switzerland \n |url=http://www.purina.com/company/Danforth.aspx \n |accessdate=2009-10-19 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629001151/http://www.purina.com/company/Danforth.aspx \n |archivedate=June 29, 2010 \n}}  </ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n*[[Louisville sewer explosions]]\n*[[Ralcorp]]\n*[[Purina Mills]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|http://www.purina.com }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080801191735/http://purina.mobi/ Purina Mobile Website]\n* [http://www.cargill.com/feed/brands/purina/index.jsp Cargill's Purina division (international animal feed brand)]\n* [http://www.agripurina.ca Agribrands Purina Canada Inc. (Canada animal feed brand)]\n* [http://www.ralcorp.com Ralcorp]\n* [http://www.poultrynutrition.com Purina Mills Poultry Nutrition]\n* [https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/petcentric/id365214222?mt=8 Purina iPhone App]\n* [http://appworld.blackberry.com/webstore/content/7445 Purina BlackBerry App]\n\n{{Nestl\u00e9}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ralston Purina}}\n[[Category:Ralston Purina products| 01]]\n[[Category:Defunct manufacturing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1894]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1894]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Missouri]]\n[[Category:2001 disestablishments in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Dog food brands]]\n[[Category:Cat food brands]]\n[[Category:Nestl\u00e9 brands]]\n[[Category:2001 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the Ralston portion of the now defunct Ralston Purina Company|Ralcorp}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name = Ralston Purina Company\n| logo = [[Image:Lg checker.svg|centre||160px]]\n| caption = \n| fate = Acquired by [[Nestl\u00e9]]; merged into Nestl\u00e9's pet food business\n| successor = [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare]]\n| foundation = {{Start date and age|1894|01|08}} (as [[Purina Mills]])\n| founder = [[William H. Danforth]]\n| defunct = {{End date|2001|12|12}}\n| location_city = [[St. Louis, Missouri|St. Louis]], [[Missouri]]\n| location_country = [[United States|USA]]\n| industry = Food, pet food, animal feeds\n| products = [[Dog food]], [[cat food]], [[animal health]] products, [[breakfast cereal]], [[crisp bread]]\n}}\n\n'''Ralston Purina Company''' was a [[St. Louis, Missouri]]\u2013based American [[Compound feed|animal feed]], food and [[pet food]] company. On December 12, 2001, it [[merger|merged]] with [[Switzerland|Swiss]] food-giant [[Nestl\u00e9|Nestl\u00e9's]] [[Friskies PetCare Company|Friskies]] division to form [[Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare|Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare Company]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.purina.com/|title=Purina: Nutritious Dog and Cat Food for Your Pet|website=www.purina.com}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nRalston Purina (originally  Ralston-Purina) traces its roots to 1894, when founder [[William H. Danforth]] established the animal feed company [[Purina Mills]]. Danforth, formed a partnership with George Robinson; William Andrews, entered the business of feeding farm animals by founding the Robinson-Danforth Commission Company. Its predominant brand for each animal was generally referred to as \"Chow\"; hence \"Purina Horse Chow\", \"Purina [[Dog Chow]]\", \"Purina Cat Chow\", \"Purina Rabbit Chow\", \"Purina Pig Chow\", and \"Purina Monkey Chow\".  \n\nLater, the company began producing cereal, which received endorsement by [[Webster Edgerly]], founder of [[Ralstonism]], to market Ralston [[breakfast cereals]]. Edgerly was at the time promoting the consumption of whole-grain cereal. These cereals became so successful that the name of the enterprise was changed in 1902 to the Ralston-Purina Company.<ref name=\"Washington City Paper\">{{Citation\n  | last = Carman\n  | first = Tim\n  | author-link = | last2 =\n  | first2 =\n  | author2-link =\n  | title = Food History Potpourri: Ralston Purina's D.C. Roots\n  | newspaper = Washington City Paper\n  | pages =\n  | date = 2009-04-16\n  | url = http://www.washingtoncitypaper.com/blogs/youngandhungry/2009/04/16/food-history-potpourri-ralston-purinas-dc-roots/\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-19\n}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.purina-arabia.com/meet-purina/history|title=History of Ralston Purina|publisher=Purina}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986, Ralston Purina sold Purina Mills, its US animal feed business, to [[British Petroleum]]. Purina Mills is now owned by [[Land O'Lakes]]. In 1994, the Ralston \"human food\" operations of the Ralston Purina Company were spun off into a new company called [[Ralcorp|Ralcorp Holdings]]. In 1998, Ralston Purina spun off its international animal feed business as Agribrands, which was acquired by [[Cargill]] in 2001.<ref>[http://www.cargill.com/feed/about/history/index.jsp History] at Cargill.com</ref> The animal feed businesses continue to use the Purina and Chow brands, which Purina Mills and Cargill license for use in the US and internationally, respectively.\n\n===Merger with Nestl\u00e9===\nRalston Purina became the subject of an acquisition bid by [[Switzerland|Swiss]]-based [[Nestl\u00e9]], whose [[Friskies]] brand was the other leading US brand of pet food.  Nestl\u00e9 S.A. and Ralston Purina announced in January 2001 a definitive merger agreement.<ref name=\"Forbes\">{{cite news\n  | last = Ackman\n  | first = Dan\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Nestle Seals Ralston Deal\n  | newspaper = Forbes\n  | location =\n  | pages = \n  | date = 2001-01-16\n  | url = https://www.forbes.com/2001/01/16/0116dogfood.html\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-19}}</ref> Under the agreement, Nestl\u00e9 acquired all of Ralston Purina's (NYSE: RAL) outstanding shares for US$33.50 per share in cash. The offer represented a premium of 36% over the closing price on Friday, January 12, 2001. The transaction had an [[enterprise value]] of US$10.3 billion ($10.0 billion equity plus $1.2 billion of net debt, minus $0.9 billion of financial investments).\n\nBoth corporations saw this major strategic transaction as the ideal way to benefit from their combined know-how, complementary strengths, and international presence in the growing pet-care market.{{Citation needed|date=April 2014}} Several brands of pet food (e.g., \"[[Meow Mix]]\") had to be divested separately to meet [[antitrust]] concerns. Purina brands are now made and marketed by a division of Nestl\u00e9 (Nestl\u00e9 Purina PetCare) which is still headquartered in St. Louis.\n\nWhile primarily a pet-food company, Ralston Purina also made some other pet-related products, such as [[Tidy Cats]] brand and Yesterday's News [[cat litter]], which is made from recycled newspaper, purchased from [[Edward Lowe Industries]] in 1990. Also, Purina has honoured several Canadian animals every year since 1968 in their Animal Hall of Fame. The latest inductees included a police service dog which \"rushed and subdued an armed robber\".\n\n==Acquisitions and diversifications==\n\nIn 1977, Ralston Purina acquired Missouri Arena Corporation and the [[St. Louis Blues]] [[National Hockey League]] franchise.  During the company's ownership of the team, they changed the name of the [[St. Louis Arena]] to the Checkerdome, reflecting the Ralston Purina logo.  The franchise was sold to Harry Ornest on July 27, 1983.\n\nRalston Purina purchased the [[Energizer Holdings|Eveready Battery Company]] in 1986, owner of the Eveready and Energizer brands. The company was spun off in 2000.\n\nRalston Purina purchased [[Continental Baking Company]], makers of [[Wonder bread]] and [[Hostess (brand)|Hostess cakes]], from [[ITT Corporation|ITT]] in 1984.  Ralston spun off Continental Baking Company, subsequently bought by Irving, Texas\u2013based [[Interstate Bakeries Corporation|Interstate Brands Corporation]] (IBC).\n\nRalston Purina opened test market pizza stores called Checkerboard Pizza in 1986. The format was similar to Domino's and Little Caesars.  They opened the stores in markets such as Moorhead, Minnesota, to test how the Midwestern market would accept the concept.  They did well, but Ralston Purina decided not to enter the pizza franchise business and closed all pilots by late 1987.\n   \nRalston Purina owned and further developed the Keystone ski resort in Colorado.  The \"Checkerboard\" slope for kids and beginners at Keystone still bears their logo.\n\nRalston Purina also owned [[Jack in the Box]] fast food restaurants from 1968 to 1985,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jackintheboxinc.com/company/history|title=Jack In The Box Inc. - Our Company|publisher=}}</ref> along with several high-end restaurants.\n\nRalston Purina owned [[Van Camp Sea Food Company]] from 1963 to 1988, a tuna cannery with Chicken of the Sea as its main product.\n\nRalston Purina owned an animal pharmaceutical company in the 1970s and 1980s.\n\n==Logo==\nRalston Purina's \"checkerboard\" [[trademark]] was introduced in 1902.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://stltoday.newspapers.com/image/142210749|title=Ralston Purina Evolved from a Small Store|date=February 16, 1964|work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|access-date=March 19, 2018}}</ref> <ref>{{Cite book|title=Nestl\u00e9 in the United States: A Celebration of Good Food, Good Life|last=Rodengen|first=Jeffrey|publisher=Write Stuff Enterprises, LLC|year=2016|isbn=9781932022704|location=Fort Lauderdale, FL|pages=101}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|title=Ralston Chronicle, 1894-1994: A Century of Managing Change|last=|first=|publisher=Ralston Purina Company|year=1994|isbn=|location=Saint Louis, MO|pages=i}}</ref> It was inspired by [[William_H._Danforth|William Danforth]]'s childhood memory of a family dressed in clothing made from the same bolt of checkerboard cloth.<ref name=\"Purina History\">{{cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = A Glimpse from the Past to the Present\n  | work =\n  | publisher = Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Produits Nestl\u00e9 S.A., Vevey, Switzerland\n  | date =\n  | url = http://nestlepurinacareers.com/CultureBenefits/PurinaHistory.aspx\n  | format =\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate = 2009-10-19}}</ref> The company's headquarters was called Checkerboard Square. Danforth used the design as the visualization of a concept put forth in his book ''I Dare You'', in which he proposed that four key components in life (\"Physical\", \"Mental\", \"Social\", and \"Religious\") need to be in balance, and one area was not to develop at the expense of the others.<ref name=\"I Dare You\">{{cite book\n  | last = Danforth\n  | first = William\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = I Dare You!\n  | publisher = Kessinger Publishing, LLC\n  | date =\n  | location =\n  | pages =\n  | url =\n  | doi =\n  | id =\n  | isbn = 0-7661-2786-9}}</ref> In 1921, the design inspired the design of feed that was pressed in cubes, called \"checkers\".<ref name=\"Danforth Profile\">{{cite web\n |title=William H. Danforth, Founder \n |publisher=Soci\u00e9t\u00e9 des Produits Nestl\u00e9 S.A., Vevey, Switzerland \n |url=http://www.purina.com/company/Danforth.aspx \n |accessdate=2009-10-19 \n |url-status=dead \n |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100629001151/http://www.purina.com/company/Danforth.aspx \n |archivedate=June 29, 2010 \n}}  </ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Companies}}\n*[[Louisville sewer explosions]]\n*[[Ralcorp]]\n*[[Purina Mills]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official|http://www.purina.com }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20080801191735/http://purina.mobi/ Purina Mobile Website]\n* [http://www.cargill.com/feed/brands/purina/index.jsp Cargill's Purina division (international animal feed brand)]\n* [http://www.agripurina.ca Agribrands Purina Canada Inc. (Canada animal feed brand)]\n* [http://www.ralcorp.com Ralcorp]\n* [http://www.poultrynutrition.com Purina Mills Poultry Nutrition]\n* [https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/petcentric/id365214222?mt=8 Purina iPhone App]\n* [http://appworld.blackberry.com/webstore/content/7445 Purina BlackBerry App]\n\n{{Nestl\u00e9}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ralston Purina}}\n[[Category:Ralston Purina| 01]]\n[[Category:Animal food manufacturers]]\n[[Category:Ralston Purina products| 01]]\n[[Category:Pet food brands]]\n[[Category:Defunct manufacturing companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Manufacturing companies based in St. Louis]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 1894]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1894]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies disestablished in 2001]]\n[[Category:1894 establishments in Missouri]]\n[[Category:2001 disestablishments in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Defunct companies based in Missouri]]\n[[Category:Dog food brands]]\n[[Category:Cat food brands]]\n[[Category:Nestl\u00e9 brands]]\n[[Category:2001 mergers and acquisitions]]\n", "name_user": "GentlemanGhost", "label": "safe", "comment": "Articles generally should not be in both a category and a sub-category, seeWP:SUBCAT", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ralston_Purina"}
{"title_page": "Milton Bradley (baseball)", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{other uses|Milton Bradley (disambiguation)}}\n{{Use American English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Milton Bradley\n| image         = Milton Bradley, 2008 All-Star.jpg\n| caption       = Bradley at the 2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game\n| position      = [[Outfielder]]\n| bats          = Switch\n| throws        = Right\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1978|4|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Harbor City, California]]\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = July 19\n| debutyear     = 2000\n| debutteam     = Montreal Expos\n| finalleague   = MLB\n| finaldate     = May 8\n| finalyear     = 2011\n| finalteam     = Seattle Mariners\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value    = .271\n| stat2label    = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value    = 125\n| stat3label    = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value    = 481\n| teams         = \n* [[Montreal Expos]] ({{mlby|2000}}\u2013{{mlby|2001}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2001}}\u2013{{mlby|2003}})\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2005}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n| awards        = \n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2008]])\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flagu|United States}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1999 Pan American Games|1999 Winnipeg]] | [[Baseball at the 1999 Pan American Games|Team]] }}\n}}\n'''Milton Obelle Bradley, Jr.''' (born April 15, 1978) is an American retired professional [[baseball]] [[outfielder]]. Standing {{convert|6|ft|m}} and weighing {{convert|215|lb|kg}}, Bradley was a [[switch hitter]] who threw right-handed. During an 11-year career in [[Major League Baseball]], Bradley played with the [[Montreal Expos]] (2000\u201301), [[Cleveland Indians]] (2001\u201303), [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] (2004\u201305), [[Oakland Athletics]] (2006\u201307), [[San Diego Padres]] (2007), [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] (2008), [[Chicago Cubs]] (2009), and [[Seattle Mariners]] (2010\u201311). His career was also marred by legal troubles and several notable on-field incidents.\n\nBorn in [[Harbor City, California]], Bradley attended [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School]] before he was drafted by the Expos in the [[1996 Major League Baseball draft]]. After playing four seasons of [[minor league baseball]] for the organization, he made his major league debut on July 19, 2000. In 2001, Bradley was traded to the Cleveland Indians in exchange for pitching [[prospect (sports)|prospect]] [[Zach Day]]; he was again traded in 2004 to the Los Angeles Dodgers. After playing in 216 games for the Dodgers, the most among all teams he has played for, Bradley was traded to the Oakland Athletics for [[Andre Ethier]]. Bradley was traded to the Padres in 2007, was granted [[free agent|free agency]] after one season with the team, and signed with the Texas Rangers in 2007. He was voted to the 2008 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] with the Rangers, and led the American League with a .436 [[on-base percentage]] and a .999 [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage. For the year, Bradley finished 17th in American League [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.\n\nAfter becoming a free agent, Bradley signed with the Chicago Cubs in January 2009, who traded him in December of that year to the Seattle Mariners. In Seattle, Bradley batted .205 in 2010 and .218 in 2011 before he was released by the club. He has a career [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .271 with 135 [[home run]]s and 481 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 1,042 games played, and was described as having \"power, speed, a strong arm and star qualities\", although \"his temper \u2026 has never allowed him to fulfill his immense potential.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley All Smiles While Playing Cleveland |agency=[[Associated Press]] |last=Withers |first=Tom |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224235446/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2016 |date=March 25, 2005|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon, and was sentenced to 32 months in prison.\n\n==Early life==\nBradley was born on April 15, 1978, in Harbor City, California.<ref>{{Cite book|last=Prospectus|first=Baseball|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OsgRQcR8YHcC&pg=PA86|title=Baseball Prospectus 2010|date=February 22, 2010|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-0-470-55840-9|pages=86|language=en}}</ref> His mother, Charlena Rector, worked as a clerk at a local [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]] supermarket,<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1574709&type=story |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |title=Bradley knows only one way \u2014 the hard way |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |date=July 9, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\">{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espnmag/story?id=3747583 |title=Milton Bradley knows you think he'll explode. He's out to prove you wrong |newspaper=[[ESPN The Magazine]] |last=Keown |first=Tim |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> while his father, Milton Bradley Sr., was a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]], and was awarded a [[Purple Heart]] for his service.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> Bradley was named Milton Bradley Jr. when Milton Bradley Sr. filled out his son's birth certificate without Rector's permission.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> According to Bradley Jr.'s mother, Bradley Sr. was addicted to [[cocaine]], physically abused her, and was homeless for several years.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> Growing up, Bradley had four half-siblings from Rector's previous marriage.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |title=Two Texas All-Stars Check Their Extra Baggage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/sports/baseball/13spotlight.html?pagewanted=all |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |date=July 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBradley played baseball at Long Beach Polytechnic High School, and was a teammate of [[Chase Utley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=In Chase Utley's case, a star was formed |date=October 31, 2009 |last1=Baxter |first1=Kevin |last2=Bolch |first2=Ben |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/31/sports/sp-world-series31 |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After graduating high school with a 3.7 [[Grade point average#United States|grade point average]],<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\" /> he committed to [[California State University, Long Beach]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Baseball in Long Beach |last=Meigs |first=Tom |page=97 |year=2008 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-0-7385-5823-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=404elIgZwbAC}}</ref> but instead signed with the Expos on July 1, 1996 after being drafted by the team in the second round of the 1996 Major League Baseball draft.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Major League Baseball career==\n\n===Montreal Expos (1996\u20132001)===\nBradley began his professional baseball career with the [[GCL Expos]] of the [[Gulf Coast League]] in 1996; in 32 games, he batted .241 with 27 [[hit (baseball)|hits]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=1e899210 |title=1996 GCL Expos |work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> The following season, he played nine games for the GCL Expos and 50 for the [[Vermont Expos]], a [[short season]] affiliate of the Montreal Expos. For the Expos, he was named to the postseason [[New York\u2013Penn League]] All-Star team.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley |work=MLB.com |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=150396#gameType=%27R%27&sectionType=career&statType=1&season=2012&level=%27ALL%27 |accessdate=May 5, 2012}} Note: Click \"Bio\" for more information</ref> In 1998, he played for the [[Cape Fear Crocs]] and the [[Jupiter Hammerheads]], tying for the Croc team lead in [[double (baseball)|doubles]] with 21 while hitting .302 for the Crocs and .287 for the Hammerheads.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=ebc8a460 |title=1998 Cape Fear Crocs |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=7e1e3456 |title=1998 Jupiter Hammerheads |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> While playing for the [[Harrisburg Senators]] the next season, he was suspended seven games for starting a fight after he had been hit by a pitch.<ref>{{cite web |title=Expos unload Bradley, Urbina |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/07/31/expos010731.html |date=August 1, 2001 |work=[[CBC.ca]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He also played for the silver-medal-winning United States in the [[1999 Pan American Games]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nFinishing 76\u201366, the Senators played the [[Norwich Navigators]] for the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] championship. The series was tied two games to two in a best-of-five series. In the final game, Bradley hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] with two outs and a [[full count]], in the bottom of the ninth inning, to give the Senators a 12\u201311 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Harrisburg, Tribe's Bradley was once a Hero, Outfielder's Dramatic Grand Slam Brought Senators their 4th Consecutive Eastern League Championship |newspaper=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |page=D4 |date=May 26, 2002 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AK&s_site=ohio&p_multi=AK&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F3D7FE9A1378663&p_field_direct-0=document_id |accessdate=January 29, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During the next season, after playing in 88 games for the [[Ottawa Lynx]], he was promoted to the major league club and made his MLB debut on July 19, 2000. In his debut, he hit three straight [[single (baseball)|singles]] against the [[New York Mets]];<ref>{{cite news |title=Mets rally past Expos |newspaper=[[Record-Journal]] |publisher=The White Family |page=12 |date=July 20, 2000 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4f1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ugINAAAAIBAJ&pg=2568,2880117 |accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref> and for the season, he batted .221 with 15 RBI over 42 games played.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFor the 2001 Expos, Bradley played 67 games, including one on April 26 in which he [[base on balls|walked]] to give the Expos the [[Glossary of baseball (G)#go-ahead run|go-ahead run]] against [[Rick Ankiel]] of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in the top of the 15th inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2001/B04260SLN2001.htm |title=Montreal Expos 4, St. Louis Cardinals 3 |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref> On July 31 of that year, he was traded to the Cleveland Indians to serve as a possible replacement for [[Kenny Lofton]]; in exchange, the Expos received right-handed pitcher Zach Day.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\" /> Speaking to the [[Associated Press]] about the trade, Indians [[General Manager]] [[John Hart (baseball)|John Hart]] stated:\n\n{{quote|In Milton Bradley we are getting a top-of-the-order, middle-of-the-diamond player we feel will have a major impact at the major-league level in the near future.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\">{{cite news |title=Indians get center fielder |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=August 1, 2001 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SYkNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fHADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5714,143990 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n===Cleveland Indians (2001\u20132003)===\n[[File:M.bradley2003.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley as a Cleveland Indian]]\nAfter the deal, Bradley was assigned to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Buffalo Bisons]] and reported to the team on August 2.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley Impresses Tribe Exec |newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 5, 2001 |last=Harrington |first=Mike |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EDBF384B4C3451B&p_field_direct-0=document_id|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In addition to the 30 games he played for the Bisons, he also played 10 games for the major league Indians.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn April 15, 2002, he was placed on the [[disabled list]] (DL) following an [[appendectomy]] a day earlier at [[St. Anthony's Hospital (St. Petersburg, Florida)|St. Anthony's Hospital]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley has appendectomy |date=April 15, 2002 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-08-15/sports/0208150246_1_appendectomy-babe-ruth-world-series-hyde-park |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He went on the disabled list again on May 2 with a broken [[orbit (anatomy)|orbital bone]]<ref name=\"Eye\">{{cite news |title=American League notes |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=May 29, 2002 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/121890946.html?dids=121890946:121890946&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |page=C4 |accessdate=February 4, 2012 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and a scratched [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]]<ref name=\"AP\" /> after a batted ball had bounced off the outfield wall and hit him below his left eye while he was trying to make a catch; up to that point, he was hitting .266 in 23 games.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite web |title=Indians' Bradley out indefinitely with fracture near left eye |date=May 2, 2002 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/news/2002/05/02/indians_bradley_ap/ |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After a rehabilitation stint of six games with the Bisons, he was reactivated by the Indians on June 4<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news |title=Indians activate Bradley from DL |date=June 5, 2002 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and finished the season with a .249 batting average, 38 RBIs and nine home runs.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nBradley spent the 2003 campaign with the Indians. Despite being placed on the 15-day DL with a strained right hamstring and missing the final six weeks of the season with a lower back injury, he led the team in [[stolen base]]s, with 17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030426&content_id=291178&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |title=Tribe notes: Bradley goes on DL Jody Gerut makes Major League Debut |last=Esper |first=Damin |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]] |date=April 26, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sign_\" /> On August 30, while on the DL with a back injury, he was ticketed for speeding in [[Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio]]. After being stopped, he refused the ticket and sped away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1614567 |title=Outfielder charged with fleeing after pullover |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 12, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty to speeding and fleeing charges on September 12, but was sentenced to a three-day jail term. The ruling was upheld by the [[Supreme Court of Ohio]] in December 2004.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=USA Today |title=Bradley begins serving three-day jail sentence |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/2004-12-15-legal-roundup_x.htm |date=December 15, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2003 he signed a one-year, $1.73 million contract with the Indians in order for the Indians to avoid [[salary arbitration]] with him.<ref name=\"Sign_\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1665715 |title=Bradley agrees to one-year deal |date=November 19, 2003 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> During [[spring training]], he was banned from the Indians' training camp after not running out a [[batted ball|popup]] a game earlier.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cleveland tires of Milton Bradley's games, plans trade |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b30xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s6IFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324,892959 |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |date=April 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> On April 3, 2004, he was traded to the Dodgers for [[Franklin Guti\u00e9rrez]] and a player to be named later ([[Andrew Brown (pitcher)|Andrew Brown]]); the ''[[Akron Beacon Journal]]'' later reported that manager [[Eric Wedge]] had insisted that Bradley be traded.<ref>{{cite news |title=Talkin' Tribe |page=C4 |newspaper=Akron Beacon Journal |date=April 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers (2004\u20132005)===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=When we traded for Milton, I think we knew everything that came along with it. We knew the past, we don't necessarily think that everything's going to be completely different because he came to a different place. That's fine. I would take nine Milton Bradleys if I could get them.\n |source = \u2014 Dodgers [[general manager]] [[Paul DePodesta]]<ref name=\"Quote\" />\n |width  = 30em\n |align  = right\n |style=clear:none;max-width:50%\n}}\n\nIn his first game with the Dodgers, playing [[Center fielder|center field]], Bradley went 2-for-3, with two singles and two walks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=240405119 |title=Lawrence stingy, Nevin grand for San Diego |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=April 5, 2004 |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref> On June 1, he was ejected from a game by home plate umpire [[Terry Craft]] for arguing over [[Strike zone|balls and strikes]]. After being restrained by manager [[Jim Tracy (baseball)|Jim Tracy]], he returned to the dugout and threw a ball bag onto the field.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley really, really upset |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/dodgers/2004-06-02-bradley-ejection-tantrum_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=June 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> Bradley was suspended for four games and Tracy for one game.<ref name=\"Quote\">{{cite web |title=Outfielder also fined; Tracy suspended 1 game |date=June 4, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1815331 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> On September 19, he hit a 479-foot home run against the [[Colorado Rockies]] in [[Coors Field]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> On September 28, during a home game against the Rockies, Bradley mishandled a [[line drive]] and was charged with an [[error (baseball)|error]]. A fan threw a bottle at Bradley, who left his position in right field, picked up the bottle and threw it into the stands, yelling at the fan. Bradley was immediately ejected from the game. The next day, MLB suspended him for the remainder of the season and fined him an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley also fined for tossing the bottle into stands |date=September 30, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1891679 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> In postseason play, he hit .273 with a home run while the Dodgers lost the [[National League Division Series]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] three games to one.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2004_NLDS1.shtml |title=2004 League Division Series |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> He finished the 2004 season batting .267 with 19 home runs and 67 RBIs, but was [[caught stealing]] 11 times, tying for eighth most in MLB.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2004-batting-leaders.shtml |title=2004 Major League Baseball Batting Leaders |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the offseason, Bradley went through [[anger management]] counseling.<ref>{{cite news |title=Milton Bradley Looks to Be a Role Model |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172237/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 9, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In a game against the [[San Francisco Giants]] on April 12, 2005, he drove in two runs with a single to tie the game in the bottom of the ninth inning with two outs, the winning run then scoring on [[Jason Ellison]]'s error in the same play.<ref>{{cite news |title=This is Just the Start |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924125825/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=April 13, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Dodgers 9, San Francisco Giants 8 |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2005/B04120LAN2005.htm |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> On August 25, 2005, after hitting .290 with 38 RBIs in 75 games, he was put on the 15-day DL with a torn [[patellar tendon]] and [[anterior cruciate ligament]] which rendered him inactive for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dodgers place Milton Bradley on disabled list |date=August 25, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=2143154 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On December 13, 2005, the Dodgers traded him to the Oakland Athletics along with [[infielder]] [[Antonio P\u00e9rez (baseball)|Antonio P\u00e9rez]] for outfielder prospect [[Andre Ethier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20051213&content_id=1281508&vkey=hotstove2005&fext=.jsp&affiliateId=CommentWidget |title=A's get Bradley, Perez in deal with LA |last=Urban |first=Mychael |work=MLB.com |date=December 23, 2005 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Athletics (2006\u20132007)===\nIn his first season with the Oakland Athletics, Bradley posted a .276 batting average with 14 home runs and 52 [[runs batted in]], in a part-time role. He went on the 15-day DL on May 11, 2006 for a strained oblique muscle and a sprained right knee.<ref>{{cite news |title=AL Notes: Athletics activate Bradley, Witasick |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/default/article/AL-Notes-Athletics-activate-Bradley-Witasick-1205506.php |date=June 6, 2006 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On July 30, he hit a three-run walk-off home run to beat the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley calls the winning shot: The often maligned outfielder's ninth-inning blast bails out Street for the A's sixth walk-off win of the year |last=Roderick |first=Joe |newspaper=[[Contra Costa Times]] |publisher=[[MediaNews Group]] |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610220631/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 10, 2014 |date=July 31, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During game four of the [[2006 American League Championship Series]] versus the [[Detroit Tigers]], Bradley became the third player in MLB history to hit home runs from each side of the plate in a postseason game, joining [[Bernie Williams]] and [[Chipper Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20061011&content_id=1708819&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley's historic game can't boost A's |work=MLB.com |date=October 12, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> For the series, he went nine-for-eighteen with two home runs and five RBIs.<ref name=\"Rangers\">{{cite web |title=Rangers finalize one-year contract with Bradley |url=http://texas.rangers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071213&content_id=2324580&vkey=pr_tex&fext=.jsp&c_id=tex |work=MLB.com |date=December 17, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2007, the Athletics [[designated for assignment|designated him for assignment]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Urban |first=Mychael |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070621&content_id=2040883&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=A's designate Bradley for assignment |work=MLB.com |date=June 21, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> A trade completed the next day, which would have sent Bradley to the [[Kansas City Royals]] for [[Leo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], was voided by the Royals because he had sustained an oblique injury in his last game as an Athletic.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaegel |first=Dick |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070622&content_id=2043699&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley-to-Royals deal voided |work=MLB.com |date=June 22, 2007 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref> He was then traded to the San Diego Padres on June 29, with cash, in exchange for Andrew Brown; it was the second time those two players had been traded for each other.\n\n===San Diego Padres (2007)===\n{{multiple image\n| footer=Bradley with the Padres, broke his bat over his knee after striking out on August 28, 2007.\n| align=left\n| image1=Milton Bradley breaking the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt1=Milton Bradley before\n| width1=144\n| image2=Milton Bradley broke the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt2=Milton Bradley after\n| width2=150\n}}\nBradley started his tenure with the Padres on the 15-day DL, but came off it on July 7; in July, he batted .364 with four home runs and 12 RBI in 18 games.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\nOn September 23, 2007, however, he tore his right [[anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] while being restrained by Padres manager [[Bud Black]] during an altercation with [[first base]] [[Umpire (baseball)|umpire]] [[Mike Winters]].<ref name=\"Padres\">{{cite news |title=Padres' Bradley tears ACL in fracas\u2013 Injury ends his season; blowup starts in dispute over outfielder's ejection |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924190543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Commercial Appeal]] |date=September 25, 2007 |last=Wilson |first=Bernie |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Home plate]] umpire [[Brian Runge]] reportedly told Bradley that Winters said that he had tossed his bat in Runge's direction in a previous [[at-bat]].<ref name=\"Padres\" /> After Bradley reached first base, he questioned Winters about the alleged bat throwing and subsequent communication with Runge. According to Bradley and Padres first base coach [[Bobby Meacham]], Winters addressed Bradley with a barrage of profanity.<ref name=\"Padres\" /> Bradley then moved towards Winters. While restrained by Black, Bradley fell to the ground and injured himself. He missed the final week of the regular season in 2007, during which the Padres lost to the [[Colorado Rockies]] in a [[2007 National League Wild Card tie-breaker game|one game playoff]] for the [[Major League Baseball wild card|National League wild card]] on October 1.<ref>{{cite news |title=Going Low, Standing Tall; Rockies' 3-Run Rally in 13th Inning Stuns Padres, Secures NL Wild Card |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200233/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=October 2, 2007 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Crandall |first=Kate |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nWinters was suspended for the remainder of the season and also spent the postseason on the restricted list for the incident, after MLB determined that he had indeed directed obscene language toward Bradley. Bradley was not suspended, MLB finding no need for such discipline since he did not make physical contact with Winters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3050020 |title=Pads' Bradley fined, not suspended in blow-up with umpire |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=October 5, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Texas Rangers (2008)===\nAfter the 2007 season, Bradley agreed to a one-year contract with the Texas Rangers. He announced in early January 2008 that he expected to be healthy and ready to play in the season opener.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3160349 |title=Rehabbing torn ACL, Bradley plans to play in Rangers' opener |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs the Rangers [[designated hitter]], he led the AL in on-base plus slugging with a .999 mark. He was third in batting average (.321), and led the league in [[on-base percentage]] (.443). On making the All-Star game, he stated, \"If I somehow miraculously made it to the All-Star Game, I would be floored. I'd really be totally humbled by that. I'm just happy right now to play, to produce and to be with a good group of guys.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519222902/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archivedate=May 19, 2009 |title=Star glows, ballots grow for Texas Rangers' Bradley |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |last=Cowlishaw |first=Tim |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009}}</ref> He was selected to play in his first All-Star Game in 2008 as a designated hitter (DH) after being officially selected as a DH reserve, but due to an injury to [[David Ortiz]] he became the starting DH in the [[2008 MLB All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All-Star Game starting lineups |date=July 15, 2008 |newspaper=The Buffalo News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' Bradley attempted to confront [[Kansas City Royals]] television announcer [[Ryan Lefebvre]] in the [[press box]] following a June 2008 game for what he believed were unfair comments made on the air. As the Rangers' designated hitter, Bradley watched the broadcast when he was not batting and took offense to a comparison Lefebvre made between him and [[Josh Hamilton]].<ref name=\"BQuote\" /> Manager [[Ron Washington]] and [[general manager]] [[Jon Daniels]] chased after him and stopped him before he got to Lefebvre, at which point he returned to the clubhouse in tears and said:\n\n{{quote|All I want to do is play baseball and make a better life for my kid than I had, that's it. I love all you guys. \u2026 I'm strong, but I'm not that strong.<ref name=\"BQuote\" />}}\n\nHe was quoted by Rangers radio broadcasters as saying that he never intended to physically harm Lefebvre but did want to speak to him; Daniels said he was upset that someone he didn't know was judging him.<ref name=\"BQuote\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |title=Texas Rangers' Bradley gets emotional over TV comments |newspaper=The Dallas Morning News |last=Durrett |first=Richard |date=June 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614234953/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |archivedate=June 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Cubs (2009)===\nOn January 8, 2009, Bradley signed a three-year, $30 million deal with the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090108&content_id=3736641&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |title='Blessed' Bradley signs with Cubs |work=MLB.com |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref> He was issued a two-game suspension for supposedly making contact with umpire [[Larry Vanover]] while arguing a strike call on April 16, which was reduced to one game on appeal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |title=Bradley's suspension reduced |date=May 14, 2009 |work=MLB.com |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090514&content_id=4730876&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> During an interleague game against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on June 12, he caught a routine fly in right field and threw it into the stands, believing it was the third out of the inning when there were only two outs.<ref name='bradley-twins' /> The umpire allowed each of the Twins' baserunners to advance two bases as a result.<ref name='bradley-twins'>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/chi-13-cubs-twins-chicago-jun13,0,3738172.story |last=van Dyck |first=Dave |title=Chicago Cubs fall 7\u20134 to Minnesota Twins |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=June 13, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLater that month, Cub manager [[Lou Piniella]] told Bradley to leave the dugout and go home after he \"went after\" a [[Gatorade]] cooler in frustration after flying out in another interleague game, against the [[Chicago White Sox]]. Piniella and Bradley later confronted each other in the locker room and exchanged words.<ref name='bradley-lou'>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Seligman |title=Soto homer lifts Cubs over White Sox |date=June 27, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041611/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 27, 2009|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Piniella later apologized to Bradley, and reinserted him back into the lineup during the team's next start.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley: 'I don't have problem with Lou' |date=June 28, 2009 |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/news/story?id=4291786 |work=ESPN |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2009, the Cubs announced that Bradley would be suspended for the remainder of the season after an interview in which Bradley talked about \"negativity\" on the part of the Cub organization and declared, \"You understand why they [the Cubs] haven't won in 100 years here.\" He also said he was uncomfortable just being on the Cubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/mlb/news/story?id=4490125 |title=Chicago Cubs suspend Milton Bradley for the rest of the season |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref> General Manager [[Jim Hendry]] felt the comments were disrespectful.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Paul |title=Bradley suspended for rest of season |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=September 20, 2009 |url=http://blogs.chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports_hardball/2009/09/bradley-not-with-cubs-hendry-will-address-team.html |accessdate=September 20, 2009}}</ref> Bradley later apologized to the Cubs organization for his remarks.<ref name=\"Bradley_apologize\">{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Morrissey |title=Here's a 'real' apology from Milton Bradley |date=September 25, 2009 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-09-25/sports/0909250004_1_apology-milton-bradley-alfonso-soriano |accessdate=September 25, 2009}}</ref> For the Cubs, Bradley hit .257 with 12 home runs and 40 RBIs<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> before being traded to the Seattle Mariners for [[Carlos Silva]] and cash on December 18, 2009.<ref name='bradley-trade1'>{{cite news |first=Larry |last=Stone |title=Shocker: Mariners trade Carlos Silva for Milton Bradley |date=December 18, 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thehotstoneleague/2010540975_shocker_mariners_trading_carlo.html |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Mariners (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Milton Bradley speaks to the ump.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley speaking to umpire [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]]]]\nBradley was part of a flurry of offseason moves by the Mariners in hopes of returning to the playoffs, having not reached the postseason since 2001.<ref name=\"Cubs trade Bradley\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091218&content_id=7828862&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc&partnerId=rss_chc |title=Cubs trade Bradley for Silva, cash |last=Muskat |first=Carrie |work=MLB.com |accessdate=December 18, 2009}}</ref> On May 4, 2010, he removed himself from a game and left the stadium. He asked the Mariners for help with a personal problem, and the organization responded. He was placed on the restricted list, and returned to the team on May 18 after undergoing treatment of an undisclosed nature.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/troubled-milton-bradley-placed-on-mariners-restricted-list/1 |title=Troubled Milton Bradley placed on Mariners' restricted list |newspaper=USA Today |last=Nightengale |first=Bob |date=May 6, 2010 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> He ended the season on the DL after having been placed on it on July 31 prior to right knee [[arthroscopic]] surgery on August 17. He finished the 2010 season batting .205, with eight home runs and 29 RBIs over 73 games played.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nOn May 9, 2011, the Mariners designated Bradley for assignment after starting the 2011 season hitting .218 with two home runs and 13 RBI in 28 games. Reportedly, the Mariners lost patience with Bradley due to his performance in a series against the White Sox. In the first game, he was ejected for arguing balls and strikes in the eighth inning, preventing the Mariners from putting in a pinch-runner due to not having enough available players. In the second game, he was booed for not hustling after several balls hit his way. In the final game, he made a poor throw that led to two White Sox runs.<ref name=\"nwsource1\">{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |title=Mariners cut ties with Milton Bradley |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514005616/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref> Unable to trade Bradley, the Mariners released him on May 16.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2005, Bradley was the Dodgers' nominee for the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] for working with the Dodgers Dream Foundation, [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]], and the Long Beach [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Clubs]], among other charities. Bradley has also opened two baseball academies, one in Long Beach and another in [[Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles|Baldwin Hills]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Milton Bradley |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308082647/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |archivedate=March 8, 2009 |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |work=MLB.com |accessdate=May 6, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2005, [[Redondo Beach, California|Redondo Beach]] police received three domestic-violence-related calls from Bradley's house. No charges were filed.<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Domestic Calls to Bradley's Home |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172455/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=August 31, 2005 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2006, Bradley filed for divorce but the petition was never finalized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley, wife will meet for hearing; Mariners; Bradley, wife to meet in L.A. to determine if felony case proceeds |date=February 10, 2011 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152832/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, Bradley was arrested at his home in [[Encino, California]] and charged with making criminal threats to his wife, Monique. When he agreed to participate in an out-of-court hearing process, no charges were filed against him. However, his wife subsequently filed for divorce.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" /><ref>Bradley was arrested in August 2011 for allegedly attacking Monique with a bat, and in March 2012 he allegedly threatened her with a knife and while yelling profanities. Monique filed a domestic violence report with the LAPD in November 2012 claiming Bradley tried to choke her, with two hands, when she asked him to stop smoking marijuana in front of their sons.\nOn January 10, 2013, Bradley was formerly charged by LAPD with 13 misdemeanor counts of assault with a deadly weapon, vandalism and dissuading a witness from making a report. {{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-193023686--mlb.html1 |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |date=January 11, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Bradley was charged with several crimes stemming from five different domestic incidents which occurred in 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former MLB outfielder Milton Bradley charged with domestic abuse |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2013/01/11/milton-bradley-charged-in-la-with-domestic-abuse/1827619/ |accessdate=June 4, 2017 |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2013 |language=en}}</ref> On June 3, 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon. On July 2, 2013, he was sentenced to 32 months in prison and 52 weeks of domestic violence and anger-management classes, and was released on $250,000 bail.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/04/08/milton-bradley-domestic-abuse-mlb-monique-bradley |title=The tragic extent of Monique and Milton Bradley's violent relationship |last=McKnight |first=Michael |date=April 13, 2015 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=April 15, 2015}}</ref> Despite his convictions and sentence, Bradley maintained [[sole custody]] of his and Monique's two sons.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=A's Bradley Files for Divorce |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172638/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=January 12, 2006 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |agency=Associated Press|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"AP_2013\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-abuse}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2013, at the age of 33, Monique Bradley died<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ohio/obituary.aspx?pid=167158640#fbLoggedOut Monique Bradley Obituary - Akron, OH | Akron Beacon Journal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> at [[Encino Hospital Medical Center]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[death certificate]] dated October 10 lists the causes as [[Cryptogenic disease|cryptogenic]] [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]], [[Shock (circulatory)|hemorrhagic shock]] and [[cardiac arrest]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn January 21, 2015, a Los Angeles [[appellate court]] rejected Bradley's appeal.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' reported in May 2015 that following another unsuccessful appeal, Bradley was ordered to begin serving the 32-month sentence for his 2013 convictions, with the hearing judge stating that Bradley's request for leniency was \"breathtaking, frankly, in how callous\" it was.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley to start serving 32-month jail sentence |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/05/15/milton-bradley-jail-domestic-abuse |work=Sports Illustrated |date=May 15, 2015 |accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref> In early 2016, Bradley's request to have his jail sentence reduced was denied by a Los Angeles Superior Court judge.<ref>{{cite web |title=Judge denies request by ex-MLB OF Milton Bradley for reduced jail time |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/01/07/milton-bradley-release-court-case |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 7, 2016 |accessdate=April 17, 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Bradley was charged with spousal battery and taken into custody on bail of $175,000 for allegedly assaulting his wife during a January 2018 incident, at which time Bradley was on probation for his earlier domestic violence conviction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley Charged With Spousal Battery |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2018/04/09/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-spousal-battery |work=Sports Illustrated |date=April 9, 2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley Handcuffed In Court at Domestic Violence Hearing |url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/04/10/milton-bradley-handcuffed-custody-battery-domestic-violence/ |work=TMZ |date=April 10, 2018 |accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018 Bradley pleaded no contest to domestic battery, was sentenced to 36 months of probation, and was required to complete 52 weeks of domestic violence counseling.<ref>{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley Convicted in Dom. Violence Case |url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/06/13/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-convicted/ |work=TMZ |date=June 13, 2018 |accessdate=August 14, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Milton Bradley}}\n{{commonscat|Milton Bradley (baseball)}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=150396 |espn=4245 |br=b/bradlmi01 |fangraphs=369 |brm=bradle001mil}}\n{{Good article}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Milton}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1999 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cape Fear Crocs players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Expos players]]\n[[Category:Harrisburg Senators players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas 51s players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball outfielders]]\n[[Category:Montreal Expos players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of battery]]\n[[Category:People from Harbor City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sacramento River Cats players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Stockton Ports players]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Vermont Expos players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{other uses|Milton Bradley (disambiguation)}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name          = Milton Bradley\n| image         = Milton Bradley, 2008 All-Star.jpg\n| caption       = Bradley at the 2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game\n| position      = [[Outfielder]]\n| bats          = Switch\n| throws        = Right\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|mf=yes|1978|4|15}}\n| birth_place   = [[Harbor City, California]]\n| debutleague   = MLB\n| debutdate     = July 19\n| debutyear     = 2000\n| debutteam     = Montreal Expos\n| finalleague   = MLB\n| finaldate     = May 8\n| finalyear     = 2011\n| finalteam     = Seattle Mariners\n| statleague    = MLB\n| stat1label    = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value    = .271\n| stat2label    = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value    = 125\n| stat3label    = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value    = 481\n| teams         = \n* [[Montreal Expos]] ({{mlby|2000}}\u2013{{mlby|2001}})\n* [[Cleveland Indians]] ({{mlby|2001}}\u2013{{mlby|2003}})\n* [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] ({{mlby|2004}}\u2013{{mlby|2005}})\n* [[Oakland Athletics]] ({{mlby|2006}}\u2013{{mlby|2007}})\n* [[San Diego Padres]] ({{mlby|2007}})\n* [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] ({{mlby|2008}})\n* [[Chicago Cubs]] ({{mlby|2009}})\n* [[Seattle Mariners]] ({{mlby|2010}}\u2013{{mlby|2011}})\n| awards        = \n* [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2008 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2008]])\n|medaltemplates=\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]] }}\n{{MedalCountry | {{flagu|United States}} }}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[Pan American Games]] }}\n{{MedalSilver | [[1999 Pan American Games|1999 Winnipeg]] | [[Baseball at the 1999 Pan American Games|Team]] }}\n}}\n\n'''Milton Obelle Bradley, Jr.''' (born April 15, 1978) is an American retired professional [[baseball]] [[outfielder]]. Standing {{convert|6|ft|m}} and weighing {{convert|215|lb|kg}}, Bradley was a [[switch hitter]] who threw right-handed. During an 11-year career in [[Major League Baseball]], Bradley played with the [[Montreal Expos]] (2000\u201301), [[Cleveland Indians]] (2001\u201303), [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] (2004\u201305), [[Oakland Athletics]] (2006\u201307), [[San Diego Padres]] (2007), [[Texas Rangers (baseball)|Texas Rangers]] (2008), [[Chicago Cubs]] (2009), and [[Seattle Mariners]] (2010\u201311). His career was also marred by legal troubles and several notable on-field incidents.\n\nBorn in [[Harbor City, California]], Bradley attended [[Long Beach Polytechnic High School]] before he was drafted by the Expos in the [[1996 Major League Baseball draft]]. After playing four seasons of [[minor league baseball]] for the organization, he made his major league debut on July 19, 2000. In 2001, Bradley was traded to the Cleveland Indians in exchange for pitching [[prospect (sports)|prospect]] [[Zach Day]]; he was again traded in 2004 to the Los Angeles Dodgers. After playing in 216 games for the Dodgers, the most among all teams he has played for, Bradley was traded to the Oakland Athletics for [[Andre Ethier]]. Bradley was traded to the Padres in 2007, was granted [[free agent|free agency]] after one season with the team, and signed with the Texas Rangers in 2007. He was voted to the 2008 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game]] with the Rangers, and led the American League with a .436 [[on-base percentage]] and a .999 [[on-base plus slugging]] percentage. For the year, Bradley finished 17th in American League [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] voting.\n\nAfter becoming a free agent, Bradley signed with the Chicago Cubs in January 2009, who traded him in December of that year to the Seattle Mariners. In Seattle, Bradley batted .205 in 2010 and .218 in 2011 before he was released by the club. He has a career [[batting average (baseball)|batting average]] of .271 with 135 [[home run]]s and 481 [[runs batted in]] (RBIs) in 1,042 games played, and was described as having \"power, speed, a strong arm and star qualities\", although \"his temper \u2026 has never allowed him to fulfill his immense potential.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley All Smiles While Playing Cleveland |agency=[[Associated Press]] |last=Withers |first=Tom |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224235446/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106731484.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=February 24, 2016 |date=March 25, 2005|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon, and was sentenced to 32 months in prison.\n\n==Early life==\nBradley was born on April 15, 1978, in Harbor City, California. His mother, Charlena Rector, worked as a clerk at a local [[Safeway Inc.|Safeway]] supermarket,<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/print?id=1574709&type=story |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |title=Bradley knows only one way \u2014 the hard way |publisher=[[ESPN]] |accessdate=January 28, 2011 |date=July 9, 2003}}</ref><ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\">{{cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espnmag/story?id=3747583 |title=Milton Bradley knows you think he'll explode. He's out to prove you wrong |newspaper=[[ESPN The Magazine]] |last=Keown |first=Tim |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref> while his father, Milton Bradley Sr., was a veteran of the [[Vietnam War]], and was awarded a [[Purple Heart]] for his service.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> Bradley was named Milton Bradley Jr. when Milton Bradley Sr. filled out his son's birth certificate without Rector's permission.<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_1\" /> According to Bradley Jr.'s mother, Bradley Sr. was addicted to [[cocaine]], physically abused her, and was homeless for several years.<ref name=\"NYT\" /> Growing up, Bradley had four half-siblings from Rector's previous marriage.<ref name=\"NYT\">{{cite news |title=Two Texas All-Stars Check Their Extra Baggage |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/07/13/sports/baseball/13spotlight.html?pagewanted=all |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |last=Schwarz |first=Alan |date=July 13, 2008 |accessdate=January 28, 2011}}</ref>\n\nBradley played baseball at Long Beach Polytechnic High School, and was a teammate of [[Chase Utley]].<ref>{{cite news |title=In Chase Utley's case, a star was formed |date=October 31, 2009 |last1=Baxter |first1=Kevin |last2=Bolch |first2=Ben |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]] |url=http://articles.latimes.com/2009/oct/31/sports/sp-world-series31 |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After graduating high school with a 3.7 [[Grade point average#United States|grade point average]],<ref name=\"Ealy_Life_2\" /> he committed to [[California State University, Long Beach]],<ref>{{cite book |title=Baseball in Long Beach |last=Meigs |first=Tom |page=97 |year=2008 |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |isbn=978-0-7385-5823-3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=404elIgZwbAC}}</ref> but instead signed with the Expos on July 1, 1996 after being drafted by the team in the second round of the 1996 Major League Baseball draft.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Major League Baseball career==\n\n===Montreal Expos (1996\u20132001)===\nBradley began his professional baseball career with the [[GCL Expos]] of the [[Gulf Coast League]] in 1996; in 32 games, he batted .241 with 27 [[hit (baseball)|hits]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=1e899210 |title=1996 GCL Expos |work=[[Baseball-Reference.com]] |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> The following season, he played nine games for the GCL Expos and 50 for the [[Vermont Expos]], a [[short season]] affiliate of the Montreal Expos. For the Expos, he was named to the postseason [[New York\u2013Penn League]] All-Star team.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley |work=MLB.com |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/team/player.jsp?player_id=150396#gameType=%27R%27&sectionType=career&statType=1&season=2012&level=%27ALL%27 |accessdate=May 5, 2012}} Note: Click \"Bio\" for more information</ref> In 1998, he played for the [[Cape Fear Crocs]] and the [[Jupiter Hammerheads]], tying for the Croc team lead in [[double (baseball)|doubles]] with 21 while hitting .302 for the Crocs and .287 for the Hammerheads.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=ebc8a460 |title=1998 Cape Fear Crocs |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/minors/team.cgi?id=7e1e3456 |title=1998 Jupiter Hammerheads |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=January 29, 2012}}</ref> While playing for the [[Harrisburg Senators]] the next season, he was suspended seven games for starting a fight after he had been hit by a pitch.<ref>{{cite web |title=Expos unload Bradley, Urbina |url=http://www.cbc.ca/sports/story/2001/07/31/expos010731.html |date=August 1, 2001 |work=[[CBC.ca]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He also played for the silver-medal-winning United States in the [[1999 Pan American Games]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nFinishing 76\u201366, the Senators played the [[Norwich Navigators]] for the [[Eastern League (baseball)|Eastern League]] championship. The series was tied two games to two in a best-of-five series. In the final game, Bradley hit a [[Walk-off home run|walk-off]] [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]] with two outs and a [[full count]], in the bottom of the ninth inning, to give the Senators a 12\u201311 win.<ref>{{cite news |title=In Harrisburg, Tribe's Bradley was once a Hero, Outfielder's Dramatic Grand Slam Brought Senators their 4th Consecutive Eastern League Championship |newspaper=[[Akron Beacon Journal]] |page=D4 |date=May 26, 2002 |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=AK&s_site=ohio&p_multi=AK&p_theme=realcities&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0F3D7FE9A1378663&p_field_direct-0=document_id |accessdate=January 29, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During the next season, after playing in 88 games for the [[Ottawa Lynx]], he was promoted to the major league club and made his MLB debut on July 19, 2000. In his debut, he hit three straight [[single (baseball)|singles]] against the [[New York Mets]];<ref>{{cite news |title=Mets rally past Expos |newspaper=[[Record-Journal]] |publisher=The White Family |page=12 |date=July 20, 2000 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=4f1IAAAAIBAJ&sjid=ugINAAAAIBAJ&pg=2568,2880117 |accessdate=January 30, 2012}}</ref> and for the season, he batted .221 with 15 RBI over 42 games played.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nFor the 2001 Expos, Bradley played 67 games, including one on April 26 in which he [[base on balls|walked]] to give the Expos the [[Glossary of baseball (G)#go-ahead run|go-ahead run]] against [[Rick Ankiel]] of the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] in the top of the 15th inning.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2001/B04260SLN2001.htm |title=Montreal Expos 4, St. Louis Cardinals 3 |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=February 2, 2012}}</ref> On July 31 of that year, he was traded to the Cleveland Indians to serve as a possible replacement for [[Kenny Lofton]]; in exchange, the Expos received right-handed pitcher Zach Day.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\" /> Speaking to the [[Associated Press]] about the trade, Indians [[General Manager]] [[John Hart (baseball)|John Hart]] stated:\n\n{{quote|In Milton Bradley we are getting a top-of-the-order, middle-of-the-diamond player we feel will have a major impact at the major-league level in the near future.<ref name=\"Quote_Trade\">{{cite news |title=Indians get center fielder |newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]] |date=August 1, 2001 |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=SYkNAAAAIBAJ&sjid=fHADAAAAIBAJ&pg=5714,143990 |accessdate=February 3, 2012}}</ref>}}\n\n===Cleveland Indians (2001\u20132003)===\n[[File:M.bradley2003.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley as a Cleveland Indian]]\nAfter the deal, Bradley was assigned to the [[Triple-A (baseball)|Triple-A]] [[Buffalo Bisons]] and reported to the team on August 2.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley Impresses Tribe Exec |newspaper=[[The Buffalo News]] |date=August 5, 2001 |last=Harrington |first=Mike |url=http://nl.newsbank.com/nl-search/we/Archives?p_product=BN&p_theme=bn&p_action=search&p_maxdocs=200&p_topdoc=1&p_text_direct-0=0EDBF384B4C3451B&p_field_direct-0=document_id|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In addition to the 30 games he played for the Bisons, he also played 10 games for the major league Indians.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nOn April 15, 2002, he was placed on the [[disabled list]] (DL) following an [[appendectomy]] a day earlier at [[St. Anthony's Hospital (St. Petersburg, Florida)|St. Anthony's Hospital]] in [[St. Petersburg, Florida]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley has appendectomy |date=April 15, 2002 |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2002-08-15/sports/0208150246_1_appendectomy-babe-ruth-world-series-hyde-park |newspaper=[[Chicago Tribune]] |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> He went on the disabled list again on May 2 with a broken [[orbit (anatomy)|orbital bone]]<ref name=\"Eye\">{{cite news |title=American League notes |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |date=May 29, 2002 |url=https://pqasb.pqarchiver.com/USAToday/access/121890946.html?dids=121890946:121890946&FMT=ABS&FMTS=ABS:FT |page=C4 |accessdate=February 4, 2012 |url-access=subscription}}</ref> and a scratched [[Iris (anatomy)|iris]]<ref name=\"AP\" /> after a batted ball had bounced off the outfield wall and hit him below his left eye while he was trying to make a catch; up to that point, he was hitting .266 in 23 games.<ref name=\"SI\">{{cite web |title=Indians' Bradley out indefinitely with fracture near left eye |date=May 2, 2002 |work=[[Sports Illustrated]] |publisher=[[CNN]] |url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/baseball/news/2002/05/02/indians_bradley_ap/ |accessdate=February 4, 2012}}</ref> After a rehabilitation stint of six games with the Bisons, he was reactivated by the Indians on June 4<ref name=\"AP\">{{cite news |title=Indians activate Bradley from DL |date=June 5, 2002 |agency=Associated Press}}</ref> and finished the season with a .249 batting average, 38 RBIs and nine home runs.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nBradley spent the 2003 campaign with the Indians. Despite being placed on the 15-day DL with a strained right hamstring and missing the final six weeks of the season with a lower back injury, he led the team in [[stolen base]]s, with 17.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20030426&content_id=291178&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=null |title=Tribe notes: Bradley goes on DL Jody Gerut makes Major League Debut |last=Esper |first=Damin |work=[[MLB.com]] |publisher=[[Major League Baseball Advanced Media]] |date=April 26, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref><ref name=\"Sign_\" /> On August 30, while on the DL with a back injury, he was ticketed for speeding in [[Cuyahoga Falls, Ohio]]. After being stopped, he refused the ticket and sped away.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1614567 |title=Outfielder charged with fleeing after pullover |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 12, 2003 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> He pleaded not guilty to speeding and fleeing charges on September 12, but was sentenced to a three-day jail term. The ruling was upheld by the [[Supreme Court of Ohio]] in December 2004.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=USA Today |title=Bradley begins serving three-day jail sentence |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/2004-12-15-legal-roundup_x.htm |date=December 15, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2003 he signed a one-year, $1.73 million contract with the Indians in order for the Indians to avoid [[salary arbitration]] with him.<ref name=\"Sign_\">{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1665715 |title=Bradley agrees to one-year deal |date=November 19, 2003 |publisher=ESPN |accessdate=April 1, 2012}}</ref> During [[spring training]], he was banned from the Indians' training camp after not running out a [[batted ball|popup]] a game earlier.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cleveland tires of Milton Bradley's games, plans trade |url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=b30xAAAAIBAJ&sjid=s6IFAAAAIBAJ&pg=6324,892959 |newspaper=[[Reading Eagle]] |date=April 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 7, 2012}}</ref> On April 3, 2004, he was traded to the Dodgers for [[Franklin Guti\u00e9rrez]] and a player to be named later ([[Andrew Brown (pitcher)|Andrew Brown]]); the ''[[Akron Beacon Journal]]'' later reported that manager [[Eric Wedge]] had insisted that Bradley be traded.<ref>{{cite news |title=Talkin' Tribe |page=C4 |newspaper=Akron Beacon Journal |date=April 4, 2004}}</ref>\n\n===Los Angeles Dodgers (2004\u20132005)===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=When we traded for Milton, I think we knew everything that came along with it. We knew the past, we don't necessarily think that everything's going to be completely different because he came to a different place. That's fine. I would take nine Milton Bradleys if I could get them.\n |source = \u2014 Dodgers [[general manager]] [[Paul DePodesta]]<ref name=\"Quote\" />\n |width  = 30em\n |align  = right\n |style=clear:none;max-width:50%\n}}\n\nIn his first game with the Dodgers, playing [[Center fielder|center field]], Bradley went 2-for-3, with two singles and two walks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/recap?gameId=240405119 |title=Lawrence stingy, Nevin grand for San Diego |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=April 5, 2004 |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref> On June 1, he was ejected from a game by home plate umpire [[Terry Craft]] for arguing over [[Strike zone|balls and strikes]]. After being restrained by manager [[Jim Tracy (baseball)|Jim Tracy]], he returned to the dugout and threw a ball bag onto the field.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley really, really upset |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/dodgers/2004-06-02-bradley-ejection-tantrum_x.htm |newspaper=USA Today |date=June 2, 2004 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> Bradley was suspended for four games and Tracy for one game.<ref name=\"Quote\">{{cite web |title=Outfielder also fined; Tracy suspended 1 game |date=June 4, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1815331 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> On September 19, he hit a 479-foot home run against the [[Colorado Rockies]] in [[Coors Field]].<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> On September 28, during a home game against the Rockies, Bradley mishandled a [[line drive]] and was charged with an [[error (baseball)|error]]. A fan threw a bottle at Bradley, who left his position in right field, picked up the bottle and threw it into the stands, yelling at the fan. Bradley was immediately ejected from the game. The next day, MLB suspended him for the remainder of the season and fined him an undisclosed amount.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley also fined for tossing the bottle into stands |date=September 30, 2004 |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=1891679 |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> In postseason play, he hit .273 with a home run while the Dodgers lost the [[National League Division Series]] to the [[St. Louis Cardinals]] three games to one.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/postseason/2004_NLDS1.shtml |title=2004 League Division Series |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 9, 2012}}</ref> He finished the 2004 season batting .267 with 19 home runs and 67 RBIs, but was [[caught stealing]] 11 times, tying for eighth most in MLB.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/MLB/2004-batting-leaders.shtml |title=2004 Major League Baseball Batting Leaders |work=Baseball-Reference.com |accessdate=April 8, 2012}}</ref>\n\nDuring the offseason, Bradley went through [[anger management]] counseling.<ref>{{cite news |title=Milton Bradley Looks to Be a Role Model |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172237/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-106202774.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 9, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In a game against the [[San Francisco Giants]] on April 12, 2005, he drove in two runs with a single to tie the game in the bottom of the ninth inning with two outs, the winning run then scoring on [[Jason Ellison]]'s error in the same play.<ref>{{cite news |title=This is Just the Start |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924125825/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-131473440.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[Los Angeles Daily News]] |date=April 13, 2005 |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Los Angeles Dodgers 9, San Francisco Giants 8 |url=http://www.retrosheet.org/boxesetc/2005/B04120LAN2005.htm |publisher=[[Retrosheet]] |accessdate=June 17, 2012}}</ref> On August 25, 2005, after hitting .290 with 38 RBIs in 75 games, he was put on the 15-day DL with a torn [[patellar tendon]] and [[anterior cruciate ligament]] which rendered him inactive for the remainder of the season.<ref>{{cite web |title=Dodgers place Milton Bradley on disabled list |date=August 25, 2005 |publisher=ESPN |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/espn/wire?section=mlb&id=2143154 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On December 13, 2005, the Dodgers traded him to the Oakland Athletics along with [[infielder]] [[Antonio P\u00e9rez (baseball)|Antonio P\u00e9rez]] for outfielder prospect [[Andre Ethier]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20051213&content_id=1281508&vkey=hotstove2005&fext=.jsp&affiliateId=CommentWidget |title=A's get Bradley, Perez in deal with LA |last=Urban |first=Mychael |work=MLB.com |date=December 23, 2005 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Athletics (2006\u20132007)===\nIn his first season with the Oakland Athletics, Bradley posted a .276 batting average with 14 home runs and 52 [[runs batted in]], in a part-time role. He went on the 15-day DL on May 11, 2006 for a strained oblique muscle and a sprained right knee.<ref>{{cite news |title=AL Notes: Athletics activate Bradley, Witasick |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/default/article/AL-Notes-Athletics-activate-Bradley-Witasick-1205506.php |date=June 6, 2006 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> On July 30, he hit a three-run walk-off home run to beat the [[Toronto Blue Jays]] with two outs in the bottom of the ninth inning.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley calls the winning shot: The often maligned outfielder's ninth-inning blast bails out Street for the A's sixth walk-off win of the year |last=Roderick |first=Joe |newspaper=[[Contra Costa Times]] |publisher=[[MediaNews Group]] |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140610220631/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-148863240.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=June 10, 2014 |date=July 31, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> During game four of the [[2006 American League Championship Series]] versus the [[Detroit Tigers]], Bradley became the third player in MLB history to hit home runs from each side of the plate in a postseason game, joining [[Bernie Williams]] and [[Chipper Jones]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20061011&content_id=1708819&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley's historic game can't boost A's |work=MLB.com |date=October 12, 2006 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref> For the series, he went nine-for-eighteen with two home runs and five RBIs.<ref name=\"Rangers\">{{cite web |title=Rangers finalize one-year contract with Bradley |url=http://texas.rangers.mlb.com/news/press_releases/press_release.jsp?ymd=20071213&content_id=2324580&vkey=pr_tex&fext=.jsp&c_id=tex |work=MLB.com |date=December 17, 2007 |accessdate=May 3, 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 21, 2007, the Athletics [[designated for assignment|designated him for assignment]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Urban |first=Mychael |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070621&content_id=2040883&vkey=news_mlb&fext=.jsp&c_id=mlb |title=A's designate Bradley for assignment |work=MLB.com |date=June 21, 2007 |accessdate=May 6, 2012}}</ref> A trade completed the next day, which would have sent Bradley to the [[Kansas City Royals]] for [[Leo N\u00fa\u00f1ez]], was voided by the Royals because he had sustained an oblique injury in his last game as an Athletic.<ref>{{cite web |last=Kaegel |first=Dick |url=http://oakland.athletics.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20070622&content_id=2043699&vkey=news_oak&fext=.jsp&c_id=oak |title=Bradley-to-Royals deal voided |work=MLB.com |date=June 22, 2007 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref> He was then traded to the San Diego Padres on June 29, with cash, in exchange for Andrew Brown; it was the second time those two players had been traded for each other.\n\n===San Diego Padres (2007)===\n{{multiple image\n| footer=Bradley with the Padres, broke his bat over his knee after striking out on August 28, 2007.\n| align=left\n| image1=Milton Bradley breaking the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt1=Milton Bradley before\n| width1=144\n| image2=Milton Bradley broke the bat over his knee after striking out.jpg\n| alt2=Milton Bradley after\n| width2=150\n}}\nBradley started his tenure with the Padres on the 15-day DL, but came off it on July 7; in July, he batted .364 with four home runs and 12 RBI in 18 games.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\nOn September 23, 2007, however, he tore his right [[anterior cruciate ligament|ACL]] while being restrained by Padres manager [[Bud Black]] during an altercation with [[first base]] [[Umpire (baseball)|umpire]] [[Mike Winters]].<ref name=\"Padres\">{{cite news |title=Padres' Bradley tears ACL in fracas\u2013 Injury ends his season; blowup starts in dispute over outfielder's ejection |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924190543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-21794923.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |newspaper=[[The Commercial Appeal]] |date=September 25, 2007 |last=Wilson |first=Bernie |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> [[Home plate]] umpire [[Brian Runge]] reportedly told Bradley that Winters said that he had tossed his bat in Runge's direction in a previous [[at-bat]].<ref name=\"Padres\" /> After Bradley reached first base, he questioned Winters about the alleged bat throwing and subsequent communication with Runge. According to Bradley and Padres first base coach [[Bobby Meacham]], Winters addressed Bradley with a barrage of profanity.<ref name=\"Padres\" /> Bradley then moved towards Winters. While restrained by Black, Bradley fell to the ground and injured himself. He missed the final week of the regular season in 2007, during which the Padres lost to the [[Colorado Rockies]] in a [[2007 National League Wild Card tie-breaker game|one game playoff]] for the [[Major League Baseball wild card|National League wild card]] on October 1.<ref>{{cite news |title=Going Low, Standing Tall; Rockies' 3-Run Rally in 13th Inning Stuns Padres, Secures NL Wild Card |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924200233/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-7637760.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=October 2, 2007 |newspaper=[[The Washington Post]] |last=Crandall |first=Kate |accessdate=June 19, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nWinters was suspended for the remainder of the season and also spent the postseason on the restricted list for the incident, after MLB determined that he had indeed directed obscene language toward Bradley. Bradley was not suspended, MLB finding no need for such discipline since he did not make physical contact with Winters.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3050020 |title=Pads' Bradley fined, not suspended in blow-up with umpire |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=October 5, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Texas Rangers (2008)===\nAfter the 2007 season, Bradley agreed to a one-year contract with the Texas Rangers. He announced in early January 2008 that he expected to be healthy and ready to play in the season opener.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/mlb/news/story?id=3160349 |title=Rehabbing torn ACL, Bradley plans to play in Rangers' opener |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=December 18, 2007 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref>\n\nAs the Rangers [[designated hitter]], he led the AL in on-base plus slugging with a .999 mark. He was third in batting average (.321), and led the league in [[on-base percentage]] (.443). On making the All-Star game, he stated, \"If I somehow miraculously made it to the All-Star Game, I would be floored. I'd really be totally humbled by that. I'm just happy right now to play, to produce and to be with a good group of guys.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090519222902/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/stories/060608dnspocowlishaw.3022001.html?npc |archivedate=May 19, 2009 |title=Star glows, ballots grow for Texas Rangers' Bradley |newspaper=[[The Dallas Morning News]] |last=Cowlishaw |first=Tim |date=June 6, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009}}</ref> He was selected to play in his first All-Star Game in 2008 as a designated hitter (DH) after being officially selected as a DH reserve, but due to an injury to [[David Ortiz]] he became the starting DH in the [[2008 MLB All-Star Game]].<ref>{{cite news |title=All-Star Game starting lineups |date=July 15, 2008 |newspaper=The Buffalo News}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Dallas Morning News]]'' Bradley attempted to confront [[Kansas City Royals]] television announcer [[Ryan Lefebvre]] in the [[press box]] following a June 2008 game for what he believed were unfair comments made on the air. As the Rangers' designated hitter, Bradley watched the broadcast when he was not batting and took offense to a comparison Lefebvre made between him and [[Josh Hamilton]].<ref name=\"BQuote\" /> Manager [[Ron Washington]] and [[general manager]] [[Jon Daniels]] chased after him and stopped him before he got to Lefebvre, at which point he returned to the clubhouse in tears and said:\n\n{{quote|All I want to do is play baseball and make a better life for my kid than I had, that's it. I love all you guys. \u2026 I'm strong, but I'm not that strong.<ref name=\"BQuote\" />}}\n\nHe was quoted by Rangers radio broadcasters as saying that he never intended to physically harm Lefebvre but did want to speak to him; Daniels said he was upset that someone he didn't know was judging him.<ref name=\"BQuote\">{{cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |title=Texas Rangers' Bradley gets emotional over TV comments |newspaper=The Dallas Morning News |last=Durrett |first=Richard |date=June 12, 2008 |accessdate=January 4, 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080614234953/http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/dws/spt/baseball/rangers/stories/061208dnsporangersbradley.3c7e26f.html |archivedate=June 14, 2008}}</ref>\n\n===Chicago Cubs (2009)===\nOn January 8, 2009, Bradley signed a three-year, $30 million deal with the [[Chicago Cubs]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090108&content_id=3736641&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |title='Blessed' Bradley signs with Cubs |work=MLB.com |date=January 8, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2010}}</ref> He was issued a two-game suspension for supposedly making contact with umpire [[Larry Vanover]] while arguing a strike call on April 16, which was reduced to one game on appeal.<ref>{{cite web |first=Carrie |last=Muskat |title=Bradley's suspension reduced |date=May 14, 2009 |work=MLB.com |url=http://chicago.cubs.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20090514&content_id=4730876&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc |accessdate=May 4, 2012}}</ref> During an interleague game against the [[Minnesota Twins]] on June 12, he caught a routine fly in right field and threw it into the stands, believing it was the third out of the inning when there were only two outs.<ref name='bradley-twins' /> The umpire allowed each of the Twins' baserunners to advance two bases as a result.<ref name='bradley-twins'>{{cite news |url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/sports/baseball/cubs/chi-13-cubs-twins-chicago-jun13,0,3738172.story |last=van Dyck |first=Dave |title=Chicago Cubs fall 7\u20134 to Minnesota Twins |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=June 13, 2009 |accessdate=May 16, 2011}}</ref>\n\nLater that month, Cub manager [[Lou Piniella]] told Bradley to leave the dugout and go home after he \"went after\" a [[Gatorade]] cooler in frustration after flying out in another interleague game, against the [[Chicago White Sox]]. Piniella and Bradley later confronted each other in the locker room and exchanged words.<ref name='bradley-lou'>{{cite news |first=Andrew |last=Seligman |title=Soto homer lifts Cubs over White Sox |date=June 27, 2009 |agency=Associated Press |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924041611/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1A1-D992M73G0.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 27, 2009|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Piniella later apologized to Bradley, and reinserted him back into the line-up during the team's next start.<ref>{{cite web |title=Bradley: 'I don't have problem with Lou' |date=June 28, 2009 |publisher=ESPN Inc |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/news/story?id=4291786 |work=ESPN |accessdate=July 1, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn September 20, 2009, the Cubs announced that Bradley would be suspended for the remainder of the season after an interview in which Bradley talked about \"negativity\" on the part of the Cub organization and declared, \"You understand why they [the Cubs] haven't won in 100 years here.\" He also said he was uncomfortable just being on the Cubs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/chicago/mlb/news/story?id=4490125 |title=Chicago Cubs suspend Milton Bradley for the rest of the season |work=ESPN |publisher=ESPN Inc |date=September 21, 2009 |accessdate=September 27, 2009}}</ref> General Manager [[Jim Hendry]] felt the comments were disrespectful.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sullivan |first=Paul |title=Bradley suspended for rest of season |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |date=September 20, 2009 |url=http://blogs.chicagosports.chicagotribune.com/sports_hardball/2009/09/bradley-not-with-cubs-hendry-will-address-team.html |accessdate=September 20, 2009}}</ref> Bradley later apologized to the Cubs organization for his remarks.<ref name=\"Bradley_apologize\">{{cite news |first=Rick |last=Morrissey |title=Here's a 'real' apology from Milton Bradley |date=September 25, 2009 |newspaper=Chicago Tribune |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2009-09-25/sports/0909250004_1_apology-milton-bradley-alfonso-soriano |accessdate=September 25, 2009}}</ref> For the Cubs, Bradley hit .257 with 12 home runs and 40 RBIs<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" /> before being traded to the Seattle Mariners for [[Carlos Silva]] and cash on December 18, 2009.<ref name='bradley-trade1'>{{cite news |first=Larry |last=Stone |title=Shocker: Mariners trade Carlos Silva for Milton Bradley |date=December 18, 2009 |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/thehotstoneleague/2010540975_shocker_mariners_trading_carlo.html |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]] |accessdate=May 5, 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Seattle Mariners (2010\u20132011)===\n[[File:Milton Bradley speaks to the ump.jpg|thumb|right|Bradley speaking to umpire [[Joe West (umpire)|Joe West]]]]\nBradley was part of a flurry of offseason moves by the Mariners in hopes of returning to the playoffs, having not reached the postseason since 2001.<ref name=\"Cubs trade Bradley\">{{cite web |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20091218&content_id=7828862&vkey=news_chc&fext=.jsp&c_id=chc&partnerId=rss_chc |title=Cubs trade Bradley for Silva, cash |last=Muskat |first=Carrie |work=MLB.com |accessdate=18 December 2009}}</ref> On May 4, 2010, he removed himself from a game and left the stadium. He asked the Mariners for help with a personal problem, and the organization responded. He was placed on the restricted list, and returned to the team on May 18 after undergoing treatment of an undisclosed nature.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/dailypitch/post/2010/05/troubled-milton-bradley-placed-on-mariners-restricted-list/1 |title=Troubled Milton Bradley placed on Mariners' restricted list |newspaper=USA Today |last=Nightengale |first=Bob |date=May 6, 2010 |accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> He ended the season on the DL after having been placed on it on July 31 prior to right knee [[arthroscopic]] surgery on August 17. He finished the 2010 season batting .205, with eight home runs and 29 RBIs over 73 games played.<ref name=\"Bio_Personal\" />\n\nOn May 9, 2011, the Mariners designated Bradley for assignment after starting the 2011 season hitting .218 with two home runs and 13 RBI in 28 games. Reportedly, the Mariners lost patience with Bradley due to his performance in a series against the White Sox. In the first game, he was ejected for arguing balls and strikes in the eighth inning, preventing the Mariners from putting in a pinch-runner due to not having enough available players. In the second game, he was booed for not hustling after several balls hit his way. In the final game, he made a poor throw that led to two White Sox runs.<ref name=\"nwsource1\">{{cite news |last=Baker |first=Geoff |url=http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |title=Mariners cut ties with Milton Bradley |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=May 9, 2011 |accessdate=May 16, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110514005616/http://seattletimes.nwsource.com/html/mariners/2015005893_mari10.html |archivedate=May 14, 2011}}</ref> Unable to trade Bradley, the Mariners released him on May 16.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" />\n\n==Personal life==\nIn 2005, Bradley was the Dodgers' nominee for the [[Roberto Clemente Award]] for working with the Dodgers Dream Foundation, [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]], and the Long Beach [[Boys & Girls Clubs of America|Boys & Girls Clubs]], among other charities. Bradley has also opened two baseball academies, one in Long Beach and another in [[Baldwin Hills, Los Angeles|Baldwin Hills]].<ref>{{Cite web |title=Milton Bradley |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090308082647/http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |archivedate=March 8, 2009 |url=http://mlb.mlb.com/mlb/components/official_info/community/clemente_2005/bios/bradley_milton.jsp |work=MLB.com |accessdate=May 6, 2012 |url-status=dead}}</ref> In August 2005, [[Redondo Beach, California|Redondo Beach]] police received three domestic-violence-related calls from Bradley's house. No charges were filed.<ref>{{cite news |title=3 Domestic Calls to Bradley's Home |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172455/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-112655375.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=August 31, 2005 |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=June 17, 2012|url-access=subscription}}</ref> In 2006, Bradley filed for divorce but the petition was never finalized.<ref>{{cite news |title=Bradley, wife will meet for hearing; Mariners; Bradley, wife to meet in L.A. to determine if felony case proceeds |date=February 10, 2011 |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924152832/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-248777587.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |url-access=subscription}}</ref>\n\nOn January 18, 2011, Bradley was arrested at his home in [[Encino, California]] and charged with making criminal threats to his wife, Monique. When he agreed to participate in an out-of-court hearing process, no charges were filed against him. However, his wife subsequently filed for divorce.<ref name=\"nwsource1\" /><ref>Bradley was arrested in August 2011 for allegedly attacking Monique with a bat, and in March 2012 he allegedly threatened her with a knife and while yelling profanities. Monique filed a domestic violence report with the LAPD in November 2012 claiming Bradley tried to choke her, with two hands, when she asked him to stop smoking marijuana in front of their sons.\nOn January 10, 2013, Bradley was formerly charged by LAPD with 13 misdemeanor counts of assault with a deadly weapon, vandalism and dissuading a witness from making a report. {{cite web |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/news/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-193023686--mlb.html1 |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |date=January 11, 2013 |accessdate=January 16, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Bradley was charged with several crimes stemming from five different domestic incidents which occurred in 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news |title=Former MLB outfielder Milton Bradley charged with domestic abuse |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/mlb/2013/01/11/milton-bradley-charged-in-la-with-domestic-abuse/1827619/ |accessdate=4 June 2017 |work=[[USA Today]] |agency=[[Associated Press]] |date=January 11, 2013 |language=en}}</ref> On June 3, 2013, Bradley was convicted by a jury of nine counts of physically attacking and threatening his wife including four counts of spousal battery, two counts of criminal threats, one count of assault with a deadly weapon, one count of vandalism and one count of brandishing a deadly weapon. On July 2, 2013, he was sentenced to 32 months in prison and 52 weeks of domestic violence and anger-management classes, and was released on $250,000 bail.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/04/08/milton-bradley-domestic-abuse-mlb-monique-bradley |title=The tragic extent of Monique and Milton Bradley's violent relationship |last=McKnight |first=Michael |date=13 April 2015 |work=Sports Illustrated |access-date=15 April 2015}}</ref> Despite his convictions and sentence, Bradley maintained [[sole custody]] of his and Monique's two sons.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{cite news |title=A's Bradley Files for Divorce |url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924172638/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P1-117252832.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |date=January 12, 2006 |accessdate=June 18, 2012 |agency=Associated Press|url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref name=\"AP_2013\">{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley charged in LA with domestic abuse |agency=Associated Press |url=http://bigstory.ap.org/article/milton-bradley-charged-la-domestic-abuse}}</ref>\n\nOn September 14, 2013, at the age of 33, Monique Bradley died<ref>[http://www.legacy.com/obituaries/ohio/obituary.aspx?pid=167158640#fbLoggedOut Monique Bradley Obituary - Akron, OH | Akron Beacon Journal<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref> at [[Encino Hospital Medical Center]].<ref name=\":0\" /> A [[death certificate]] dated October 10 lists the causes as [[Cryptogenic disease|cryptogenic]] [[cirrhosis]] of the [[liver]], [[Shock (circulatory)|hemorrhagic shock]] and [[cardiac arrest]].<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn January 21, 2015, a Los Angeles [[appellate court]] rejected Bradley's appeal.<ref name=\":0\" /> ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'' reported in May 2015 that following another unsuccessful appeal, Bradley was ordered to begin serving the 32-month sentence for his 2013 convictions, with the hearing judge stating that Bradley's request for leniency was \"breathtaking, frankly, in how callous\" it was.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley to start serving 32-month jail sentence |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2015/05/15/milton-bradley-jail-domestic-abuse |work=Sports Illustrated |date=May 15, 2015 |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref> In early 2016, Bradley's request to have his jail sentence reduced was denied by a Los Angeles Superior Court judge.<ref>{{cite web |title=Judge denies request by ex-MLB OF Milton Bradley for reduced jail time |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2016/01/07/milton-bradley-release-court-case |work=Sports Illustrated |date=January 7, 2016 |accessdate=2017-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, Bradley was charged with spousal battery and taken into custody on bail of $175,000 for allegedly assaulting his wife during a January 2018 incident, at which time Bradley was on probation for his earlier domestic violence conviction.<ref>{{cite web |title=Ex-MLB outfielder Milton Bradley Charged With Spousal Battery |url=https://www.si.com/mlb/2018/04/09/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-spousal-battery |work=Sports Illustrated |date=2018-04-09 |accessdate=2018-08-07}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley Handcuffed In Court at Domestic Violence Hearing |url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/04/10/milton-bradley-handcuffed-custody-battery-domestic-violence/ |work=TMZ |date=2018-04-10 |accessdate=2018-08-07}}</ref> In June 2018 Bradley pleaded no contest to domestic battery, was sentenced to 36 months of probation, and was required to complete 52 weeks of domestic violence counseling.<ref>{{cite web |title=Milton Bradley Convicted in Dom. Violence Case |url=http://www.tmz.com/2018/06/13/milton-bradley-domestic-violence-convicted/ |work=TMZ |date=2018-06-13 |accessdate=2018-08-14}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote|Milton Bradley}}\n{{commonscat|Milton Bradley (baseball)}}\n{{baseballstats|mlb=150396 |espn=4245 |br=b/bradlmi01 |fangraphs=369 |brm=bradle001mil}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Milton}}\n[[Category:1978 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:African-American baseball players]]\n[[Category:Akron Aeros players]]\n[[Category:American expatriate baseball players in Canada]]\n[[Category:American League All-Stars]]\n[[Category:American people convicted of assault]]\n[[Category:American sportspeople convicted of crimes]]\n[[Category:Baseball players at the 1999 Pan American Games]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Buffalo Bisons (minor league) players]]\n[[Category:Cape Fear Crocs players]]\n[[Category:Chicago Cubs players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Indians players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Expos players]]\n[[Category:Harrisburg Senators players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Las Vegas 51s players]]\n[[Category:Los Angeles Dodgers players]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball outfielders]]\n[[Category:Montreal Expos players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Athletics players]]\n[[Category:Ottawa Lynx players]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games medalists in baseball]]\n[[Category:Pan American Games silver medalists for the United States]]\n[[Category:People convicted of battery]]\n[[Category:People from Harbor City, Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sacramento River Cats players]]\n[[Category:San Diego Padres players]]\n[[Category:Seattle Mariners players]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Stockton Ports players]]\n[[Category:Texas Rangers players]]\n[[Category:Vermont Expos players]]\n", "name_user": "Coffeeandcrumbs", "label": "safe", "comment": "+ ref, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript, American English, date formats perMOS:DATEFORMATbyscript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Milton_Bradley_(baseball)"}
{"title_page": "Stefan Ba\u0142uk", "text_new": "{{short description|Polish general and photographer}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Stefan Baluk Warsaw August27 2008 Fot Mariusz Kubik 04.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Ba\u0142uk in Warsaw (27 August 2008)\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1914|01|15|df=yes}}\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2014|01|29|1914|01|15|df=yes}}\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Soldier\n* [[taxicab]] driver }}\n| module             = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n | branch             = [[Home Army]]\n | branch_label       = Service\n | allegiance         = {{flag|Polish Underground State}}\n | unit               = {{plainlist|\n* [[10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade (Poland)|10th Cavalry Brigade]]\n* ''[[Cichociemni]]'' }}\n | battles            = {{plainlist|\n* [[World War II]]\n* {{spaces|2}}[[Invasion of Poland]]\n* {{spaces|2}}[[Warsaw Uprising]] }}\n | battles_label      = Conflicts\n | rank               = [[Genera\u0142 brygady]]\n | awards             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Virtuti Militari]]\n* [[Armia Krajowa Cross]]\n* [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] }}\n }}\n}}\n'''Stefan Ba\u0142uk''' (15 January 1914{{spaced en dash}}29 January 2014) was a Polish general and photographer.\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:Stefan Ba\u0142uk - \"Kubu\u015b\".jpg|thumb|left|Ba\u0142uk in 1944]]\nBorn on 15 January 1914, Ba\u0142uk was a [[legal education|law student]] at the [[University of Warsaw]] at the onset of [[World War II]].  After joining the [[Home Army]], Ba\u0142uk fought in the [[Invasion of Poland]], and then transferred to the [[10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade (Poland)|10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade]].  Ba\u0142uk received parachute commando training in [[Glasgow]] before being dropped back into Poland in April 1944 as ''[[Cichociemni]]''.  Ba\u0142uk \"engaged in the production of false documents for Polish intelligence officers, made photo documentation of German military installations in Warsaw and took part in the [[Warsaw Uprising]].\"<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\" />  After his release from [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] [[prisoner-of-war camp]] [[Oflag II-D]] in [[Borne Sulinowo|Gro\u00dfborn]], Ba\u0142uk traveled to his mother's and sister's home in [[Praga]]; he found their house destroyed, but with a note saying they had fled to safety<!-- commented lacking specification: in Skar\u017cysko -->.<ref name=\"2013 Warsaw 1944\" />\n\nDuring his World War II service, Ba\u0142uk was promoted to the (21st-century equivalent)<!-- as seen in the photo --> rank of [[genera\u0142 brygady]] and awarded both the [[Virtuti Militari]]<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\" /> and the [[Armia Krajowa Cross]].<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\" />\n\n==Post-war==\nAfter the war, Ba\u0142uk Was imprisoned by the [[Soviet Union]] from November 1945 to March 1947.<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\" />  He later worked as a [[taxicab]] driver and took up [[photography]] as a hobby&mdash;publishing several photo albums.  In 2008, Ba\u0142uk published his [[memoirs]]: ''By\u0142em Cichociemnym'' (released in English as ''Silent and Unseen: I Was a WWII Special Ops Commando'').<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\" />  Ba\u0142uk died on 29 January 2014.  He was posthumously awarded the Grand Cross of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] by [[President of Poland|Polish President]] [[Bronis\u0142aw Komorowski]], and later buried in [[Pow\u0105zki Military Cemetery]].<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n\n<!-- dated sources sorted chronologically -->\n\n<ref name=\"2013 Warsaw 1944\">{{cite book |last1=Richie |first1=Alexandra |year=2013 |chapter=Conclusion |title=Warsaw 1944: Hitler, Himmler, and the Warsaw Uprising |language=en |location=[[New York City]] |publisher=[[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] |page=642 |isbn=978-0-374-28655-2}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\">{{cite news |date=2014-01-15 |title=Poland's unsung war-time hero turns 100 |url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/158688 |url-status=live |language=en |publisher=[[Radio Poland]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403213439/http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/158688 |archive-date=2020-04-03 |access-date=2020-04-03 |quote=General Stefan Ba\u0142uk, one of the last living members of the elite special-operations paratroopers of Poland's WWII Home Army celebrates his 100th birthday today.}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\">{{cite news |date=2014-02-05 |title=Poland's war-time hero laid to rest |url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/161038 |url-status=live |language=en |publisher=[[Radio Poland]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403220702/http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/161038 |archive-date=2020-04-03 |access-date=2020-04-03 |quote=General Stefan Ba\u0142uk, one of the last living members of the elite special-operations paratroops of the Home Army known as \u2018Cichociemni\u2019 (Silent and Unseen), has been buried at Warsaw\u2019s Powazki Military Cemetery.}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ba\u0142uk, Stefan}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century photographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century photographers]]\n[[Category:Armia Krajowa officers]]\n[[Category:Burials at Pow\u0105zki Military Cemetery]]\n[[Category:Cichociemni]]\n[[Category:Grand Crosses of the Order of Polonia Restituta]]\n[[Category:Polish centenarians]]\n[[Category:Polish generals]]\n[[Category:Polish military personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Polish photographers]]\n[[Category:Polish prisoners of war]]\n[[Category:Polish September Campaign participants]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Armia Krajowa Cross]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Virtuti Militari (1943\u201389)]]\n[[Category:Taxicab drivers]]\n[[Category:Warsaw Uprising insurgents]]\n[[Category:World War II prisoners of war held by the Soviet Union]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Polish general and photographer}}\n{{use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| honorific_prefix   = \n| name               = <!-- use common name/article title -->\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = Stefan Baluk Warsaw August27 2008 Fot Mariusz Kubik 04.jpg\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = Ba\u0142uk in Warsaw (27 August 2008)\n| birth_date         = {{birth date|1914|01|15|df=yes}}\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2014|01|29|1914|01|15|df=yes}}\n| occupation         = {{flatlist|\n* Soldier\n* [[taxicab]] driver }}\n| module             = {{Infobox military person |embed=yes\n | branch             = [[Home Army]]\n | branch_label       = Service\n | allegiance         = {{flag|Polish Underground State}}\n | unit               = {{plainlist|\n* [[10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade (Poland)|10th Cavalry Brigade]]\n* ''[[Cichociemni]]'' }}\n | battles            = {{plainlist|\n* [[World War II]]\n* {{spaces|2}}[[Invasion of Poland]]\n* {{spaces|2}}[[Warsaw Uprising]] }}\n | battles_label      = Conflicts\n | rank               = [[Genera\u0142 brygady]]\n | awards             = {{plainlist|\n* [[Virtuti Militari]]\n* [[Armia Krajowa Cross]]\n* [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] }}\n }}\n}}\n'''Stefan Ba\u0142uk''' (15 January 1914{{spaced en dash}}29 January 2014) was a Polish general and photographer.\n\n==World War II==\n[[File:Stefan Ba\u0142uk - \"Kubu\u015b\".jpg|thumb|left|Ba\u0142uk in 1944]]\nBorn on 15 January 1914, Ba\u0142uk was a [[legal education|law student]] at the [[University of Warsaw]] at the onset of [[World War II]].  After joining the [[Home Army]], Ba\u0142uk fought in the [[Invasion of Poland]], and then transfered to the [[10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade (Poland)|10th Motorized Cavalry Brigade]].  Ba\u0142uk received parachute commando training in [[Glasgow]] before being dropped back into Poland in April 1944 as ''[[Cichociemni]]''.  Ba\u0142uk \"engaged in the production of false documents for Polish intelligence officers, made photo documentation of German military installations in Warsaw and took part in the [[Warsaw Uprising]].\"<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\" />  After his release from [[Nazi Germany|Nazi]] [[prisoner-of-war camp]] [[Oflag II-D]] in [[Borne Sulinowo|Gro\u00dfborn]], Ba\u0142uk traveled to his mother's and sister's home in [[Praga]]; he found their house destroyed, but with a note saying they had fled to safety<!-- commented lacking specification: in Skar\u017cysko -->.<ref name=\"2013 Warsaw 1944\" />\n\nDuring his World War II service, Ba\u0142uk was promoted to the (21st-century equivalent)<!-- as seen in the photo --> rank of [[genera\u0142 brygady]] and awarded both the [[Virtuti Militari]]<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\" /> and the [[Armia Krajowa Cross]].<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\" />\n\n==Post-war==\nAfter the war, Ba\u0142uk Was imprisoned by the [[Soviet Union]] from November 1945 to March 1947.<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\" />  He later worked as a [[taxicab]] driver and took up [[photography]] as a hobby&mdash;publishing several photo albums.  In 2008, Ba\u0142uk published his [[memoirs]]: ''By\u0142em Cichociemnym'' (released in English as ''Silent and Unseen: I Was a WWII Special Ops Commando'').<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\" />  Ba\u0142uk died on 29 January 2014.  He was posthumously awarded the Grand Cross of the [[Order of Polonia Restituta]] by [[President of Poland|Polish President]] [[Bronis\u0142aw Komorowski]], and later buried in [[Pow\u0105zki Military Cemetery]].<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist |refs=\n\n<!-- dated sources sorted chronologically -->\n\n<ref name=\"2013 Warsaw 1944\">{{cite book |last1=Richie |first1=Alexandra |year=2013 |chapter=Conclusion |title=Warsaw 1944: Hitler, Himmler, and the Warsaw Uprising |language=en |location=[[New York City]] |publisher=[[Farrar, Straus and Giroux]] |page=642 |isbn=978-0-374-28655-2}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2014-01-15 Radio Poland\">{{cite news |date=2014-01-15 |title=Poland's unsung war-time hero turns 100 |url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/158688 |url-status=live |language=en |publisher=[[Radio Poland]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403213439/http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/158688 |archive-date=2020-04-03 |access-date=2020-04-03 |quote=General Stefan Ba\u0142uk, one of the last living members of the elite special-operations paratroopers of Poland's WWII Home Army celebrates his 100th birthday today.}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n<ref name=\"2014-02-05 Radio Poland\">{{cite news |date=2014-02-05 |title=Poland's war-time hero laid to rest |url=http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/161038 |url-status=live |language=en |publisher=[[Radio Poland]] |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200403220702/http://archiwum.thenews.pl/1/9/Artykul/161038 |archive-date=2020-04-03 |access-date=2020-04-03 |quote=General Stefan Ba\u0142uk, one of the last living members of the elite special-operations paratroops of the Home Army known as \u2018Cichociemni\u2019 (Silent and Unseen), has been buried at Warsaw\u2019s Powazki Military Cemetery.}}</ref><!-- exhausted -->\n\n}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Commons category-inline}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ba\u0142uk, Stefan}}\n[[Category:1914 births]]\n[[Category:2014 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century photographers]]\n[[Category:21st-century photographers]]\n[[Category:Armia Krajowa officers]]\n[[Category:burials at Pow\u0105zki Military 